# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: iron-age
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:iron-age/abashevo-culture] The **Abashevo culture** (Russian: Абашевская культура, romanized: *Abashevskaya kul'tura*) is a late Middle Bronze Age archaeological culture, c.
[src:iron-age/abashevo-culture] 2200–1850 BC, found in the valleys of the middle Volga and Kama River north of the Samara bend and into the southern Ural Mountains.
[src:iron-age/abashevo-culture] It receives its name from the village of Abashevo in Chuvashia.
[src:iron-age/abashevo-culture] Tracing its origins in the Fatyanovo–Balanovo culture, an eastern offshoot of the Corded Ware culture of Central Europe, the Abashevo culture is notable for its metallurgical activity and evidence for the use of chariots in its end phase.
[src:iron-age/abashevo-culture] It eventually came to absorb the Volosovo culture.
[src:iron-age/abashevo-culture] The Abashevo culture is often viewed as pre-Indo-Iranian-speaking or Proto-Indo-Iranian-speaking.
[src:iron-age/abashevo-culture] It played a major role in the development of the Sintashta culture and Srubnaya culture.
[src:iron-age/abashevo-culture] The Abashevo culture is believed to have formed on the northern Don in the early 3rd millennium BC.
[src:iron-age/abashevo-culture] It occupied part of the area of the earlier Fatyanovo–Balanovo culture, the eastern variant of the earlier Corded Ware culture.
[src:iron-age/abashevo-culture] Influences from the Yamnaya culture and Catacomb culture on the Abashevo culture are detected.
[src:iron-age/abashevo-culture] The pre-eminent expert on the Abashevo culture, Anatoly Pryakhin, concluded that it originated from contacts between Fatyanovo–Balanovo, Catacomb and Poltavka peoples in the southern forest-steppe.
[src:iron-age/abashevo-culture] The influence of the Yamnaya culture persisted until approximately 1700 BC with the emergence of new technologies, traditions, and customs.
[src:iron-age/abashevo-culture] The Abashevo culture represents an extension of steppe culture into the forest zone.
[src:iron-age/abashevo-culture] The Abashevo culture flourished in the forest steppe areas of the middle Volga and upper Don.
[src:iron-age/abashevo-culture] The sites were represented largely by kurgan cemeteries and some areas with evidence of copper smelting.
[src:iron-age/abashevo-culture] A few settlements extended in the northern steppes of the middle Volga.
[src:iron-age/abashevo-culture] The Abashevo culture appears to have absorbed parts of the Volosovo culture.
[src:iron-age/abashevo-culture] Contacts with the Volosovo culture appears to have facilitated the spread of pastoralism and metallurgy into northern forest cultures.
[src:iron-age/abashevo-culture] The easternmost sites of the Abashevo culture are located along the southern Urals.
[src:iron-age/abashevo-culture] Those sites are associated with the origins of the Sintashta culture.
[src:iron-age/abashevo-culture] The Abashevo culture is divided into a Don-Volga variant, a middle Volga variant and a southern Ural variant.
[src:iron-age/abashevo-culture] On the northern Don, the Abashevo culture replaced the Catacomb culture.
[src:iron-age/abashevo-culture] Along the middle Volga, it co-existed with the Poltavka culture.
[src:iron-age/abashevo-culture] Kuzmina suggests that the Seima-Turbino phenomenon emerged as a result of interaction between the Abashevo culture, the Catacomb culture and the early Andronovo culture.
[src:iron-age/abashevo-culture] The type site of the Abashevo culture is at Abashevo, Chuvash Republic.
[src:iron-age/abashevo-culture] More than two hundred settlements have been found.
[src:iron-age/abashevo-culture] Houses were rectangular with large floor areas of about 150 to 200 m².
[src:iron-age/abashevo-culture] Some settlements appear to have been occupied only briefly, and just two of them appear to have been fortified.
[src:iron-age/abashevo-culture] The Abashevo culture is primarily represented by various kurgan cemeteries.
[src:iron-age/abashevo-culture] Kurgans were surrounded by a circular ditch, and the grave pit had ledges at its edges.
[src:iron-age/abashevo-culture] The body was either contracted on the side, or supine with raised knees, with legs flexed.
[src:iron-age/abashevo-culture] Its funerary customs appear to have been derived from the Poltavka culture.
[src:iron-age/abashevo-culture] Its inhumation practices in tumuli are similar to the Yamnaya culture and Fatyanovo–Balanovo culture.
[src:iron-age/abashevo-culture] Flat graves are a component of the Abashevo culture burial rite, as in the earlier Fatyanovo culture.
[src:iron-age/abashevo-culture] The kurgans of the Abashevo culture are to be distinguished from the flat graves of the Fatyanovo–Balanovo culture.
[src:iron-age/abashevo-culture] A well-known Abashevo kurgan in Pepkino contained the remains of twenty-eight males who appear to have died violent deaths.
[src:iron-age/abashevo-culture] Grave offerings are scant, little more than a pot or two usually made with crushed-shell temper.
[src:iron-age/abashevo-culture] Some graves show evidence of a birch bark floor and a timber construction forming walls and roof.
[src:iron-age/abashevo-culture] High-status Abashevo graves contain silver and copper ornaments, and weapons.
[src:iron-age/abashevo-culture] Crucibles for smelting copper and moulds for casting were found in some graves, most likely funerals reserved to bronzesmiths.
[src:iron-age/abashevo-culture] High-status Abashevo women are notable for wearing a distinctive type of headband with pendants made of copper and silver.
[src:iron-age/abashevo-culture] These headbands are unique to the Abashevo culture, and are probably an ethnic marker and symbol of political status.
[src:iron-age/abashevo-culture] The diadems of the Abashevo women are very similar to those of elite women in Mycenaean Greece.
[src:iron-age/abashevo-culture] Elena Efimovna Kuzmina cites this as evidence of cultural synchronization between these ancient cultures.
[src:iron-age/abashevo-culture] Abashevo ceramics display influences from the Catacomb culture, which was located further south.
[src:iron-age/abashevo-culture] Its ceramics in turn influence those of the Sintashta culture.
[src:iron-age/abashevo-culture] The Abashevo culture was an important center of metallurgy, as the southern Urals provided a major source of local copper.
[src:iron-age/abashevo-culture] There is evidence of copper smelting, and the culture engaged in copper mining activities, which stimulated the formation of Sintashta metallurgy.
[src:iron-age/abashevo-culture] About half of Abashevo metal objects are of copper, while the other half is of bronze.
[src:iron-age/abashevo-culture] Silver-bearing ores were also extracted, from which silver ornaments were made.
[src:iron-age/abashevo-culture] Abashevo metal types, such as knives were very similar to those of the Catacomb culture and the Poltavka culture.
[src:iron-age/abashevo-culture] The economy of the Abashevo culture was mixed agriculture.
[src:iron-age/abashevo-culture] Cattle, sheep, pig and goats, as well as other domestic animals were kept.
[src:iron-age/abashevo-culture] Stone grinders and metal sickles are evidences of agriculture.
[src:iron-age/abashevo-culture] Horses were evidently used, inferred by cheek pieces typical of neighboring steppe cultures and Mycenaean Greece.
[src:iron-age/abashevo-culture] According to Elena Kuzmina (2007) the first controlling of chariots with cheek-pieces can be attributed to the Abashevo and Multi-cordoned ware cultures.
[src:iron-age/abashevo-culture] The population of Sintashta derived their stock-breeding from Abashevo.
[src:iron-age/abashevo-culture] Abashevo cattle was of the Ukrainian Grey type, and this cattle had previously been raised among earlier Neolithic cultures of the Pontic steppe and along the Danube.
[src:iron-age/abashevo-culture] This type of cattle was later adopted by the Sintashta culture and the Srubnaya culture.
[src:iron-age/abashevo-culture] Archaeological evidence suggests that Abashevo society was intensely warlike.
[src:iron-age/abashevo-culture] Mass graves reveal that inter-tribal battles involved hundreds of warriors of both sides, which indicates a significant degree of inter-regional political integration.
[src:iron-age/abashevo-culture] Warfare appears to have been more frequent in the late Abashevo period, and it was in this turbulent environment in which the Sintashta culture emerged.
[src:iron-age/abashevo-culture] David Anthony assumes that the Abashevo people spoke Pre-Indo-Iranian or Proto-Indo-Iranian, since it is a possible source of Indo-Iranian loanwords in Uralic.
[src:iron-age/abashevo-culture] The Indo-Iranian characteristic of the Abashevo language is also evidenced in its loanwords in Finnic and Saami.
[src:iron-age/abashevo-culture] It probably witnessed a bilingual population undergo a process of assimilation.
[src:iron-age/abashevo-culture] Physical remains of the Abashevo people has revealed that they were Caucasoids/Europoids with dolichocephalic skulls.
[src:iron-age/abashevo-culture] The physical type of Abashevo, Sintashta, Andronovo and Srubnaya is later observed among the Scythians.
[src:iron-age/abashevo-culture] The Abashevo culture is closely associated with the Sintashta culture, and must have played a role in its origin.
[src:iron-age/abashevo-culture] The Sintashta culture however differs from the Abashevo culture through having fortified settlements, conducting large-scale animal sacrifices, and in its metal types and ornaments.
[src:iron-age/abashevo-culture] Continuity between the Abashevo culture and the later Srubnaya culture has been pointed out.
[src:iron-age/abashevo-culture] Along with the Potapovka culture, the Abashevo culture is considered an ancestor of the Srubnaya culture.
[src:iron-age/abashevo-culture] The Potapovka culture itself emerged from the Poltavka culture with influences from the Abashevo culture.
[src:iron-age/abusir] The pyramid complex is named after the neighbouring village of Abusir, in the markaz (county) of Badrashin, Giza.
[src:iron-age/abusir] The Abusir pyramid complex is located on the Western Desert plateau at the edge of the cultivated plain, with the Giza Pyramids to its north, and Saqqara to its south, and served as one of the main elite cemeteries for the ancient Egyptian capital city of Memphis.
[src:iron-age/abusir] Several other villages in northern and southern Egypt are named Abusir or Busiri.
[src:iron-age/abusir] The locality of Abusir took its turn as the focus of the prestigious western burial rites operating out of the then-capital of Memphis during the Old Kingdom Fifth Dynasty.
[src:iron-age/abusir] As an elite cemetery, neighbouring Giza had by then "filled up" with the massive pyramids and other monuments of the Fourth Dynasty, leading the Fifth Dynasty pharaohs to seek sites elsewhere for their own funerary monuments.
[src:iron-age/abusir] Abusir was the origin of the largest find of Old Kingdom papyri to date — the Abusir Papyri.
[src:iron-age/abusir] In the late nineteenth century, a number of Western museums acquired collections of fragmentary papyri from the administrative (temple) records of one Abusir funerary cult, that of king Neferirkare Kakai.
[src:iron-age/abusir] This discovery was supplemented in the late twentieth century when excavations by a Czech expedition to the site revealed papyri from two other cult complexes, that of the pharaoh Neferefre (also read Raneferef) and for the king's mother Khentkaus II.
[src:iron-age/abusir] The Czech Institute of Egyptology of the Faculty of Arts, Charles University in Prague has been conducting excavations at Abusir since 1960, beginning with the mastaba of Ptahshepses, directed by Zbyněk Žába.
[src:iron-age/abusir] The concession was extended since 1976 with the southern part of the royal necropolis, directed by Miroslav Verner.
[src:iron-age/abusir] Since 1991, the institute excavates also at the site of Abusir South.
[src:iron-age/abusir] The excavations are presently directed by Miroslav Bárta.
[src:iron-age/abusir] There are considerable catacombs near the ancient town of Busiris, as stated in (Pliny xxxvi.
[src:iron-age/abusir] To the south of Busiris one great cemetery appears to have stretched over the plain.
[src:iron-age/abusir] The Heptanomite Busiris was in fact a hamlet standing at one extremity of the necropolis of Memphis.
[src:iron-age/abusir] Earliest tombs on the site are from the Early Dynastic Period, First Dynasty.
[src:iron-age/abusir] Tombs, including stairway tombs, were uncovered north of pyramid field.
[src:iron-age/abusir] There are a total of four kings' pyramids at this site, which served as the main royal necropolis during the Fifth Dynasty.
[src:iron-age/abusir] The quality of construction of the Abusir pyramids is inferior to those of the Fourth Dynasty; perhaps signalling a decrease in royal power or a less vibrant economy.
[src:iron-age/abusir] They are smaller than their predecessors, and are built of low quality local stone.
[src:iron-age/abusir] A map and complete list of excavated structures until the year 2019 is available in Bárta et al.
[src:iron-age/abusir] The map is also published online as a searchable application.
[src:iron-age/abusir] Directly north of Saqqara is a cemetery of lower-ranking officials of the Early Dynastic Period and Old Kingdom.
[src:iron-age/abusir] The earliest First Dynasty tombs are on the so-called "Bonnet cemetery" named after Hans Bonnet, who published the site.
[src:iron-age/abusir] It was excavated in 1910 by Georg Steindorff and Uvo Hölscher.
[src:iron-age/abusir] Recently, copper artefacts in the collection of Leipzig University, from the site, were studied.
[src:iron-age/abusir] One vessel, ÄMUL 2162, was made of a peculiar material, arsenical copper with nickel, which could be imported to Egypt.
[src:iron-age/abusir] Also found at Abusir were substantial remains of a Ramesside temple, perhaps built by Ramses II.
[src:iron-age/abusir] The temple lies about 500 meters south east of the pyramids, close to the cultivation in the desert.
[src:iron-age/abusir] The main building of the temple was built of limestone.
[src:iron-age/abusir] There were three cellars, a small hall with four columns and a courtyard (with mudbrick walls) with ten limestone columns.
[src:iron-age/abusir] The limestone building was placed within a larger complex made of mud bricks with a pylon and magazines.
[src:iron-age/abusir] The temple seems to have been dedicated to the solar cult, in particular the gods Ra, Amun, and Nekhbet.
[src:iron-age/abusir] Fragments of polychrome reliefs and numerous examples of the titles of Ramesses II have been recovered.
[src:iron-age/abusir] The temple was built above the mud brick tombs of Third and Fifth Dynasty.
[src:iron-age/abusir] Abusir, Saqqara and Dahshur suffered damage by looters during the 2011 Egyptian protests.
[src:iron-age/abusir] Part of the false door from the tomb of the priest Rahotep was stolen, and store rooms were broken into.
[src:iron-age/abusir] The looted structures are mapped out e.g. in this article.
[src:iron-age/abusir] Köppen-Geiger climate classification system classifies its climate as hot desert (BWh), as the rest of Egypt.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] The **Achaemenid Empire** (/ə.ˈkiː.mə.nɪd/, *ə-KEE-mə-nid*; Old Persian: 𐎧𐏁𐏂, *Xšāça*, lit.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] 'The Empire' or 'The Kingdom') was an ancient Iranian empire founded by Cyrus the Great of the Achaemenid dynasty in 550 BC.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] At peak, its territorial extent was roughly 5.5 million square kilometres (2.1 million square miles), making it the largest empire of its time.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Based in the Iranian plateau, it stretched from the Balkans and Cyrenaica in the west to the Indus Valley in the east, including Anatolia, Cyprus, Mesopotamia, the Levant, the South Caucasus, parts of Eastern Arabia, and large parts of Central Asia.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] By the 7th century BC, the region of Persis, located in the southwestern part of the Iranian plateau, had been settled by Persian people.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] From Persis, Cyrus rose and defeated Media, Lydia, and the Neo-Babylonian Empire, thus marking the establishment of a new imperial polity in the ancient Near East.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] While its conquests were largely successful in most regions, the Achaemenid Empire's attempts to expand into Greece proved extremely difficult over the course of decades of wars and multiple kings, ultimately resulting in its defeat in the Greek mainland.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 330 BC, amidst a Greek military campaign that began in 336 BC, the Achaemenid Empire was conquered in its entirety by Alexander the Great, who annexed it to his Macedonian Empire.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Upon Alexander's death, which sparked the beginning of the Hellenistic period in 323 BC, the majority of the former Achaemenid Empire's territories came under the rule of the Seleucid Empire and the Ptolemaic Kingdom.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Almost a century later, Iranian elites in the central plateau successfully reclaimed power from the Seleucids and established the Parthian Empire, which existed for nearly half a millennium before being succeeded by the Iranian Sasanian Empire.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Many of these systems were adopted and expanded upon by later empires in the Greco-Roman world and beyond.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Achaemenid Empire is named after Achaemenes, who is credited as the progenitor of the Achaemenid dynasty.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] The term *Achaemenid* means "of the family of the Achaemenis/Achaemenes" (Old Persian: 𐏃𐎧𐎠𐎶𐎴𐎡𐏁, romanized: *Haxāmaniš*; a bahuvrihi compound translating to "having a friend's mind").
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Achaemenes was himself a minor seventh-century ruler of the Anshan in southwestern Iran, and a vassal of Assyria.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Around 850 BC the original nomadic people who began the empire called themselves the *Parsa* and their constantly shifting territory *Parsua*, for the most part localized around Persis.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] The name "Persia" is a Greek and Latin pronunciation of the native word referring to the country of the people originating from Persis (Old Persian: 𐎱𐎠𐎼𐎿, romanized: *Pārsa*).
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian term 𐎧𐏁𐏂 *Xšāça*, literally meaning "The Kingdom", was used to refer to the Empire formed by their multinational state.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Achaemenid Empire was created by nomadic Persians.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persians were Iranian people who arrived in what is today Iran c.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] 1000 BC and settled a region including north-western Iran, the Zagros Mountains and Persis alongside the native Elamites.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persians were originally nomadic pastoralists in the western Iranian Plateau.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Achaemenid Empire may not have been the first Iranian empire, as the Medes, another group of Iranian people, possibly established a short-lived empire when they played a major role in overthrowing the Assyrians.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Achaemenids were initially rulers of the Elamite city of Anshan near the modern city of Marvdasht; the title "King of Anshan" was an adaptation of the earlier Elamite title "King of Susa and Anshan".
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] There are conflicting accounts of the identities of the earliest Kings of Anshan.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] According to the Cyrus Cylinder (the oldest extant genealogy of the Achaemenids) the kings of Anshan were Teispes, Cyrus I, Cambyses I and Cyrus II, also known as Cyrus the Great, who founded the empire.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] The later Behistun Inscription, written by Darius the Great, claims that Teispes was the son of Achaemenes and that Darius is also descended from Teispes through a different line, but no earlier texts mention Achaemenes.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] In Herodotus' Histories, he writes that Cyrus the Great was the son of Cambyses I and Mandane of Media, the daughter of Astyages, the king of the Median Empire.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus revolted against the Median Empire in 553 BC, and in 550 BC succeeded in defeating the Medes, capturing Astyages and taking the Median capital city of Ecbatana.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Once in control of Ecbatana, Cyrus styled himself as the successor to Astyages and assumed control of the entire empire.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] By inheriting Astyages' empire, he also inherited the territorial conflicts the Medes had with both Lydia and the Neo-Babylonian Empire.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] King Croesus of Lydia sought to take advantage of the new international situation by advancing into what had previously been Median territory in Asia Minor.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus led a counterattack which not only fought off Croesus' armies, but also led to the capture of Sardis and the fall of the Lydian Kingdom in 546 BC.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus placed Pactyes in charge of collecting tribute in Lydia and left, but once Cyrus had left Pactyes instigated a rebellion against Cyrus.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus sent the Median general Mazares to deal with the rebellion, and Pactyes was captured.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Mazares, and after his death Harpagus, set about reducing all the cities which had taken part in the rebellion.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] The subjugation of Lydia took about four years in total.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] When the power in Ecbatana changed hands from the Medes to the Persians, many tributaries to the Median Empire believed their situation had changed and revolted against Cyrus.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] This forced Cyrus to fight wars against Bactria and the nomadic Saka in Central Asia.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] During these wars, Cyrus established several garrison towns in Central Asia, including the Cyropolis.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Nothing is known of Persia–Babylon relations between 547 and 539 BC, but it is likely that there were hostilities between the two empires for several years leading up to the war of 540–539 BC and the Fall of Babylon.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] In October 539 BC, Cyrus won a battle against the Babylonians at Opis, then took Sippar without a fight before finally capturing the city of Babylon on 12 October, where the Babylonian king Nabonidus was taken prisoner.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus is credited with freeing the Jews from the Babylonian captivity, permitting their return to Judah, and authorizing the rebuilding of Jerusalem, including the Second Temple.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 530 BC, Cyrus died and was succeeded by his eldest son Cambyses II, while his younger son Bardiya received a large territory in Central Asia.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] By 525 BC, Cambyses had successfully subjugated Phoenicia and Cyprus and was making preparations to invade Egypt with the newly created Persian navy.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Pharaoh Amasis II had died in 526, and had been succeeded by Psamtik III, resulting in the defection of key Egyptian allies to the Persians.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Psamtik positioned his army at Pelusium in the Nile Delta.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] He was soundly defeated by the Persians in the Battle of Pelusium before fleeing to Memphis, where the Persians defeated him and took him prisoner.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] After attempting a failed revolt, Psamtik III promptly committed suicide.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Herodotus depicts Cambyses as openly antagonistic to the Egyptian people and their gods, cults, temples, and priests, in particular stressing the murder of the sacred bull Apis.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] He says that these actions led to a madness that caused him to kill his brother Bardiya (who Herodotus says was killed in secret), his own sister-wife and Croesus of Lydia.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] He then concludes that Cambyses completely lost his mind, and all later classical authors repeat the themes of Cambyses' impiety and madness.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] However, this is based on spurious information, as the epitaph of Apis from 524 BC shows that Cambyses participated in the funeral rites of Apis styling himself as pharaoh.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Following the conquest of Egypt, the Libyans and the Greeks of Cyrene and Barca in present-day eastern Libya (Cyrenaica) surrendered to Cambyses and sent tribute without a fight.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cambyses then planned invasions of Carthage, the oasis of Ammon and Ethiopia.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Herodotus claims that the naval invasion of Carthage was canceled because the Phoenicians, who made up a large part of Cambyses' fleet, refused to take up arms against their own people, but modern historians doubt whether an invasion of Carthage was ever planned at all.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] However, Cambyses dedicated his efforts to the other two campaigns, aiming to improve the Empire's strategic position in Africa by conquering the Kingdom of Meroë and taking strategic positions in the western oases.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] To this end, he established a garrison at Elephantine consisting mainly of Jewish soldiers, who remained stationed at Elephantine throughout Cambyses' reign.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Furthermore, in two inscriptions of Darius, Nubia is listed as one of the lands in the empire, and a Nubian delegation is depicted in Persepolis on the Apadana reliefs which visually present the lands of Darius’ empire.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] These suggest that Cambyses saw success in subduing Nubia.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] The events surrounding Cambyses's death and Bardiya's succession are greatly debated as there are many conflicting accounts.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] According to Herodotus, as Bardiya's assassination had been committed in secret, the majority of Persians still believed him to be alive.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] This allowed two Magi to rise up against Cambyses, with one of them sitting on the throne able to impersonate Bardiya because of their remarkable physical resemblance and shared name (Smerdis in Herodotus's accounts).
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Ctesias writes that when Cambyses had Bardiya killed he immediately put the magus Sphendadates in his place as satrap of Bactria due to a remarkable physical resemblance.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Two of Cambyses' confidants then conspired to usurp Cambyses and put Sphendadates on the throne under the guise of Bardiya.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] According to the Behistun Inscription, written by the following king Darius the Great, a magus named Gaumata impersonated Bardiya and incited a revolution in Persia.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Whatever the exact circumstances of the revolt, Cambyses heard news of it in the summer of 522 BC and began to return from Egypt, but he was wounded in the thigh in Syria and died of gangrene, so Bardiya's impersonator became king.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] The account of Darius is the earliest, and although the later historians all agree on the key details of the story, that a magus impersonated Bardiya and took the throne, this may have been a story created by Darius to justify his own usurpation.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Iranologist Pierre Briant hypothesises that Bardiya was not killed by Cambyses, but waited until his death in the summer of 522 BC to claim his legitimate right to the throne as he was then the only male descendant of the royal family.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Briant says that although the hypothesis of a deception by Darius is generally accepted today, "nothing has been established with certainty at the present time, given the available evidence".
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] According to the Behistun inscription, Gaumata ruled for seven months before being overthrown in 522 BC by Darius the Great (Old Persian *Dāryavuš*, "who holds firm the good", also known as *Darayarahush*).
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Magi, though persecuted, continued to exist, and a year following the death of the first pseudo-Smerdis (*Gaumata*), saw a second pseudo-Smerdis (*Vahyazdāta*) attempt a coup.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] The coup, though initially successful, failed.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Herodotus writes that the native leadership debated the best form of government for the empire.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Macedonian king Amyntas I surrendered his country to the Persians in about 512–511.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] The subjugation of Macedonia was part of Persian military operations initiated by Darius the Great (521–486) in 513—after immense preparations—a huge Achaemenid army invaded the Balkans and tried to defeat the European Scythians roaming to the north of the Danube river.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Darius' army subjugated several Thracian people, and virtually all other regions that touch the European part of the Black Sea, such as parts of modern Bulgaria, Romania, Ukraine, and Russia, before it returned to Asia Minor.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Darius left in Europe one of his commanders named Megabazus whose task was to accomplish conquests in the Balkans.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian troops subjugated gold-rich Thrace, the coastal Greek cities, and defeated and conquered the powerful Paeonians.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Finally, Megabazus sent envoys to Amyntas, demanding acceptance of Persian domination, which the Macedonians did.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Balkans provided many soldiers for the multi-ethnic Achaemenid army.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Many of the Macedonian and Persian elite intermarried, such as the Persian official Bubares who married Amyntas' daughter, Gygaea.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Family ties that the Macedonian rulers Amyntas and Alexander enjoyed with Bubares ensured them good relations with the Persian kings Darius and Xerxes I, who was also known as Xerxes the Great.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian invasion led indirectly to Macedonia's rise in power and Persia had some common interests in the Balkans; with Persian aid, the Macedonians stood to gain much at the expense of some Balkan tribes such as the Paeonians and Greeks.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] All in all, the Macedonians were "willing and useful Persian allies.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Macedonian soldiers fought against Athens and Sparta in Xerxes I's army.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persians referred to both Greeks and Macedonians as *Yauna* ("Ionians", their term for "Greeks"), and to Macedonians specifically as *Yaunã Takabara* or "Greeks with hats that look like shields", possibly referring to the Macedonian kausia hat.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Ionian Revolt in 499 BC, and associated revolts in Aeolis, Doris, Cyprus, and Caria, were military rebellions by several regions of Asia Minor against Persian rule, lasting from 499 to 493 BC.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] At the heart of the rebellion was the dissatisfaction of the Greek cities of Asia Minor with the tyrants appointed by Persia to rule them, along with the individual actions of two Milesian tyrants, Histiaeus and Aristagoras.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 499 BC, the then-tyrant of Miletus, Aristagoras, launched a joint expedition with the Persian satrap Artaphernes to conquer Naxos, in an attempt to bolster his position in Miletus, both financially and in terms of prestige.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] The mission was a debacle, and sensing his imminent removal as a tyrant, Aristagoras chose to incite the whole of Ionia into rebellion against the Persian king, Darius I, who was commonly known as Darius the Great.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persians continued to reduce the cities along the west coast that still held out against them, before finally imposing a peace settlement in 493 BC on Ionia that was generally considered to be both just and fair.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Ionian Revolt constituted the first major conflict between Greece and the Achaemenid Empire, and as such represents the first phase of the Greco-Persian Wars.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Asia Minor had been brought back into the Persian fold, but Darius had vowed to punish Athens and Eretria for their support of the revolt.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Moreover, seeing that the political situation in Greece posed a continued threat to the stability of his Empire, he decided to embark on the conquest of all of Greece.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] The first campaign of the invasion was to bring the territories in the Balkan peninsula back within the empire.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian grip over these territories had loosened following the Ionian Revolt.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 492 BC, the Persian general Mardonius re-subjugated Thrace and made Macedonia a fully subordinate part of the empire; it had been a vassal as early as the late 6th century BC but retained a great deal of autonomy.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] However, in 490 BC the Persian forces were defeated by the Athenians at the Battle of Marathon and Darius I would die before having the chance to launch an invasion of Greece.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Xerxes I (485–465 BC, Old Persian *Xšayārša* "Hero Among Kings"), son of Darius I, vowed to complete the job.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] He organized a massive invasion aiming to conquer Greece.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] His army entered Greece from the north in the spring of 480 BC, meeting little or no resistance through Macedonia and Thessaly, but was delayed by a small Greek force for three days at Thermopylae.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] A simultaneous naval battle of Artemisium was tactically indecisive as large storms destroyed ships from both sides.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] The battle was stopped prematurely when the Greeks received news of the defeat at Thermopylae and retreated.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] The battle was a tactical victory for the Persians, giving them uncontested control of Artemisium and the Aegean Sea.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Following his victory at the Battle of Thermopylae, Xerxes sacked the evacuated city of Athens and prepared to meet the Greeks at the strategic Isthmus of Corinth and the Saronic Gulf.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 480 BC the Greeks won a decisive victory over the Persian fleet at the Battle of Salamis and forced Xerxes to retire to Sardis.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] The land army which he left in Greece under Mardonius retook Athens but was eventually destroyed in 479 BC at the Battle of Plataea.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] The final defeat of the Persians at Mycale encouraged the Greek cities of Asia to revolt, and the Persians lost all of their territories in Europe with Macedonia once again becoming independent.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Xerxes was assassinated in his bed, though ancient accounts conflict significantly.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] The assassination is attributed by Greek and Roman sources to Artabanus, though a Babylonian tablet attributes it to Xerxes' son.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] After Xerxes I was assassinated, he was succeeded by his eldest surviving son Artaxerxes I.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] It was during his reign that Elamite ceased to be the language of government, and Aramaic gained in importance.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] It was probably during this reign that the solar calendar was introduced as the national calendar.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Under Artaxerxes I, Zoroastrianism became the *de facto* religion of the empire.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] After Persia had been defeated at the Battle of Eurymedon (469 or 466 BC), military action between Greece and Persia was halted.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] When Artaxerxes I took power, he introduced a new Persian strategy of weakening the Athenians by funding their enemies in Greece.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] This indirectly caused the Athenians to move the treasury of the Delian League from the island of Delos to the Athenian acropolis.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] This funding practice inevitably prompted renewed fighting in 450 BC, where the Greeks attacked at the Battle of Cyprus.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] After Cimon's failure to attain much in this expedition, the Peace of Callias was agreed between Athens, Argos and Persia in 449 BC.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes offered asylum to Themistocles, who was the winner of the Battle of Salamis, after Themistocles was ostracized from Athens.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Also, Artaxerxes gave him Magnesia, Myus, and Lampsacus to maintain him in bread, meat, and wine.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] In addition, Artaxerxes I gave him Palaescepsis to provide him with clothes, and he also gave him Percote with bedding for his house.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] When Artaxerxes died in 424 BC at Susa, his body was taken to the tomb already built for him in the Naqsh-e Rustam Necropolis.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] It was Persian tradition that kings begin constructing their own tombs while they were still alive.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes I was immediately succeeded by his eldest and only legitimate son, Xerxes II.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] However, after a few days on the throne, he was assassinated while drunk by Pharnacyas and Menostanes on the orders of his illegitimate brother Sogdianus, who apparently had gained the support of his regions.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Sogdianus reigned for six months and fifteen days before being captured by his half-brother, Ochus, who had rebelled against him.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Sogdianus was executed by being suffocated in ash because Ochus had promised he would not die by the sword, by poison or by hunger.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Ochus then took the royal name Darius II.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Darius' ability to defend his position on the throne ended the short power vacuum.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] From 412 BC Darius II, at the insistence of Tissaphernes, gave support first to Athens, then to Sparta, but in 407 BC, Darius' son Cyrus the Younger was appointed to replace Tissaphernes and aid was given entirely to Sparta which finally defeated Athens in 404 BC.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] In the same year, Darius fell ill and died in Babylon.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] His death gave an Egyptian rebel named Amyrtaeus the opportunity to throw off Persian control over Egypt.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] At his death bed, Darius' Babylonian wife Parysatis pleaded with him to have her second eldest son Cyrus (the Younger) crowned, but Darius refused.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Queen Parysatis favoured Cyrus more than her eldest son Artaxerxes II.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Plutarch relates (probably on the authority of Ctesias) that the displaced Tissaphernes came to the new king on his coronation day to warn him that his younger brother Cyrus (the Younger) was preparing to assassinate him during the ceremony.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes had Cyrus arrested and would have had him executed if their mother Parysatis had not intervened.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus was then sent back as Satrap of Lydia, where he prepared an armed rebellion.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus assembled a large army, including a contingent of Ten Thousand Greek mercenaries, and made his way deeper into Persia.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] The army of Cyrus was stopped by the royal Persian army of Artaxerxes II at Cunaxa in 401 BC, where Cyrus was killed.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Ten Thousand Greek Mercenaries including Xenophon were now deep in Persian territory and were at risk of attack.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] So they searched for others to offer their services to but eventually had to return to Greece.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes II was the longest reigning of the Achaemenid kings and it was during this 45-year period of relative peace and stability that many of the monuments of the era were constructed.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes moved the capital back to Persepolis, which he greatly extended.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Also, the summer capital at Ecbatana was lavishly extended with gilded columns and roof tiles of silver and copper.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] The extraordinary innovation of the Zoroastrian shrines can also be dated to his reign, and it was probably during this period that Zoroastrianism spread from Armenia throughout Asia Minor and the Levant.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] The construction of temples, though serving a religious purpose, was not a purely selfless act, as they also served as an important source of income.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] From the Babylonian kings, the Achaemenids adopted the concept of a mandatory temple tax, a one-tenth tithe which all inhabitants paid to the temple nearest to their land or another source of income.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes II became involved in a war with Persia's erstwhile allies, the Spartans, who, under Agesilaus II, invaded Asia Minor.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] To redirect the Spartans' attention to Greek affairs, Artaxerxes II subsidized their enemies: in particular the Athenians, Thebans and Corinthians.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] These subsidies helped to engage the Spartans in what would become known as the Corinthian War.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 387 BC, Artaxerxes II betrayed his allies and came to an arrangement with Sparta, and in the Treaty of Antalcidas he forced his erstwhile allies to come to terms.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] This treaty restored control of the Greek cities of Ionia and Aeolis on the Anatolian coast to the Persians while giving Sparta dominance on the Greek mainland.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 385 BC he campaigned against the Cadusians.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Although successful against the Greeks, Artaxerxes II had more trouble with the Egyptians, who had successfully revolted against him at the beginning of his reign.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] An attempt to reconquer Egypt in 373 BC was completely unsuccessful, but in his waning years the Persians did manage to defeat a joint Egyptian–Spartan effort to conquer Phoenicia.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] He quashed the Revolt of the Satraps in 372–362 BC.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] He is reported to have had a number of wives.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] His main wife was Stateira, until she was poisoned by Artaxerxes II's mother Parysatis in about 400 BC.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Another chief wife was a Greek woman of Phocaea named Aspasia (not the same as the concubine of Pericles).
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes II is said to have had more than 115 sons from 350 wives.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 358 BC Artaxerxes II died and was succeeded by his son Artaxerxes III.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 355 BC, Artaxerxes III forced Athens to conclude a peace which required the city's forces to leave Asia Minor and to acknowledge the independence of its rebellious allies.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes started a campaign against the rebellious Cadusians, but he managed to appease both of the Cadusian kings.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] One individual who successfully emerged from this campaign was Darius Codomannus, who later occupied the Persian throne as Darius III.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes III then ordered the disbanding of all the satrapal armies of Asia Minor, as he felt that they could no longer guarantee peace in the west and was concerned that these armies equipped the western satraps with the means to revolt.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] The order was however ignored by Artabazos II of Phrygia, who asked for the help of Athens in a rebellion against the king.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Orontes of Mysia also supported Artabazos and the combined forces managed to defeat the forces sent by Artaxerxes III in 354 BC.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] However, in 353 BC, they were defeated by Artaxerxes III's army and were disbanded.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Orontes was pardoned by the king, while Artabazos fled to the safety of the court of Philip II of Macedon.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] 351 BC, Artaxerxes embarked on a campaign to recover Egypt, which had revolted under his father, Artaxerxes II.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] At the same time, a rebellion had broken out in Asia Minor, which, being supported by Thebes, threatened to become serious.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Levying a vast army, Artaxerxes invaded Egypt and engaged in fighting with Nectanebo II.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] After a year of fighting the Egyptian Pharaoh, Nectanebo inflicted a crushing defeat on the Persians with the support of mercenaries led by the Greek generals Diophantus and Lamius.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes was compelled to retreat and postpone his plans to reconquer Egypt.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Soon after this defeat, there were rebellions in Phoenicia, Asia Minor and Cyprus.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] , with a label in Greek (ΔΑΡΕΙΟΣ, top right) giving his name.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 343 BC, Artaxerxes committed responsibility for the suppression of the Cyprian rebels to Idrieus, prince of Caria, who employed 8,000 Greek mercenaries and forty triremes, commanded by Phocion the Athenian, and Evagoras, son of the elder Evagoras, the Cypriot monarch.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes initiated a counter-offensive against Sidon by commanding Belesys, satrap of Syria, and Mazaeus, satrap of Cilicia, to invade the city and to keep the Phoenicians in check.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Both satraps suffered crushing defeats at the hands of Tennes, the Sidonese king, who was aided by 40,000 Greek mercenaries sent to him by Nectanebo II and commanded by Mentor of Rhodes.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] As a result, the Persian forces were driven out of Phoenicia.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] After this, Artaxerxes personally led an army of 330,000 men against Sidon.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes' army comprised 300,000-foot soldiers, 30,000 cavalry, 300 triremes, and 500 transports or provision ships.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] After gathering this army, he sought assistance from the Greeks.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Though refused aid by Athens and Sparta, he succeeded in obtaining a thousand Theban heavy-armed hoplites under Lacrates, three thousand Argives under Nicostratus, and six thousand Æolians, Ionians, and Dorians from the Greek cities of Asia Minor.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] This Greek support was numerically small, amounting to no more than 10,000 men, but it formed, together with the Greek mercenaries from Egypt who went over to him afterward, the force on which he placed his chief reliance, and to which the ultimate success of his expedition was mainly due.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] The approach of Artaxerxes sufficiently weakened the resolution of Tennes that he endeavoured to purchase his own pardon by delivering up 100 principal citizens of Sidon into the hands of the Persian king and then admitting Artaxerxes within the defences of the town.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes had the 100 citizens transfixed with javelins, and when 500 more came out as supplicants to seek his mercy, Artaxerxes consigned them to the same fate.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Sidon was then burnt to the ground, either by Artaxerxes or by the Sidonian citizens.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Forty thousand people died in the conflagration.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes sold the ruins at a high price to speculators, who calculated on reimbursing themselves by the treasures which they hoped to dig out from among the ashes.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Tennes was later put to death by Artaxerxes.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes later sent Jews who supported the revolt to Hyrcania on the south coast of the Caspian Sea.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] The reduction of Sidon was followed closely by the invasion of Egypt.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 343 BC, Artaxerxes III, in addition to his 330,000 Persians, had now a force of 14,000 Greeks furnished by the Greek cities of Asia Minor: 4,000 under Mentor, consisting of the troops that he had brought to the aid of Tennes from Egypt; 3,000 sent by Argos; and 1,000 from Thebes.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] He divided these troops into three bodies, and placed at the head of each a Persian and a Greek.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Greek commanders were Lacrates of Thebes, Mentor of Rhodes and Nicostratus of Argos while the Persians were led by Rhossaces, Aristazanes, and Bagoas, the chief of the eunuchs.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Nectanebo II resisted with an army of 100,000 of whom 20,000 were Greek mercenaries.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Nectanebo II occupied the Nile and its various branches with his large navy.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] The character of the country, intersected by numerous canals and full of strongly fortified towns, was in his favour and Nectanebo II might have been expected to offer a prolonged, if not even a successful resistance.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] However, he lacked good generals, and, over-confident in his own powers of command, he was out-maneuvered by the Greek mercenary generals, and his forces were eventually defeated by the combined Persian armies.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] After his defeat, Nectanebo hastily fled to Memphis, leaving the fortified towns to be defended by their garrisons.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] These garrisons consisted of partly Greek and partly Egyptian troops; between whom jealousies and suspicions were easily sown by the Persian leaders.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] As a result, the Persians were able to rapidly reduce numerous towns across Lower Egypt and were advancing upon Memphis when Nectanebo decided to quit the country and flee southwards to Ethiopia.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian army completely routed the Egyptians and occupied the Lower Delta of the Nile.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Following Nectanebo fleeing to Ethiopia, all of Egypt submitted to Artaxerxes.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Jews in Egypt were sent either to Babylon or to the south coast of the Caspian Sea, the same location that the Jews of Phoenicia had earlier been sent.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] After this victory over the Egyptians, Artaxerxes had the city walls destroyed, started a reign of terror, and set about looting all the temples.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Persia gained a significant amount of wealth from this looting.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes also raised high taxes and attempted to weaken Egypt enough that it could never revolt against Persia.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] For the 10 years that Persia controlled Egypt, believers in the native religion were persecuted and sacred books were stolen.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Before Artaxerxes returned to Persia, he appointed Pherendares as satrap of Egypt.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] With the wealth gained from his reconquering Egypt, Artaxerxes was able to amply reward his mercenaries.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] He then returned to his capital having successfully completed his invasion of Egypt.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] After his success in Egypt, Artaxerxes returned to Persia and spent the next few years effectively quelling insurrections in various parts of the Empire so that a few years after his conquest of Egypt, the Persian Empire was firmly under his control.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Egypt remained a part of the Persian Empire from then until Alexander the Great's conquest of Egypt.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] After the conquest of Egypt, there were no more revolts or rebellions against Artaxerxes.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Mentor and Bagoas, the two generals who had most distinguished themselves in the Egyptian campaign, were advanced to posts of the highest importance.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Mentor, who was governor of the entire Asiatic seaboard, was successful in reducing to subjection many of the chiefs who during the recent troubles had rebelled against Persian rule.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] In the course of a few years, Mentor and his forces were able to bring the whole Asian Mediterranean coast into complete submission and dependence.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Bagoas went back to the Persian capital with Artaxerxes, where he took a leading role in the internal administration of the Empire and maintained tranquillity throughout the rest of the Empire.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] During the last six years of the reign of Artaxerxes III, the Persian Empire was governed by a vigorous and successful government.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian forces in Ionia and Lycia regained control of the Aegean and the Mediterranean Sea and took over much of Athens' former island empire.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] In response, Isocrates of Athens started giving speeches calling for a 'crusade against the barbarians' but there was not enough strength left in any of the Greek city-states to answer his call.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Although there were no rebellions in the Persian Empire itself, the growing power and territory of Philip II of Macedon in Macedon (against which Demosthenes was in vain warning the Athenians) attracted the attention of Artaxerxes.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] In response, he ordered that Persian influence was to be used to check and constrain the rising power and influence of the Macedonian kingdom.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 340 BC, a Persian force was dispatched to assist the Thracian prince, Cersobleptes, to maintain his independence.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Sufficient effective aid was given to the city of Perinthus that the numerous and well-appointed army with which Philip had commenced his siege of the city was compelled to give up the attempt.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] By the last year of Artaxerxes' rule, Philip II already had plans in place for an invasion of the Persian Empire, which would crown his career, but the Greeks would not unite with him.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 338 BC Artaxerxes was poisoned by Bagoas with the assistance of a physician.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes III was succeeded by Artaxerxes IV Arses, who before he could act was also poisoned by Bagoas.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Bagoas is further said to have killed not only all Arses' children, but many of the other princes of the land.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Bagoas then placed Darius III, a nephew of Artaxerxes IV, on the throne.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Darius III, previously the Satrap of Armenia, personally forced Bagoas to swallow poison.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 334 BC, when Darius was just succeeding in subduing Egypt again, Alexander and his battle-hardened troops invaded Asia Minor.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Alexander the Great (Alexander III of Macedon) defeated the Persian armies at Granicus (334 BC), followed by Issus (333 BC), and lastly at Gaugamela (331 BC).
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Afterwards, he marched on Susa and Persepolis which surrendered and was destroyed by fire in early 330 BC.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] From Persepolis, Alexander headed north to Pasargadae, where he visited the tomb of Cyrus, the man whom he had heard of from the *Cyropaedia*.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] In the ensuing chaos created by Alexander's invasion of Persia, Cyrus's tomb was broken into and most of its luxuries were looted.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] When Alexander reached the tomb, he was horrified by the manner in which it had been treated, and questioned the Magi, putting them on trial.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] By some accounts, Alexander's decision to put the Magi on trial was more an attempt to undermine their influence and display his own power than a show of concern for Cyrus's tomb.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Regardless, Alexander the Great ordered Aristobulus to improve the tomb's condition and restore its interior, showing respect for Cyrus.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] From there he headed to Ecbatana, where Darius III had sought refuge.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Darius III was taken prisoner by Bessus, his Bactrian satrap and kinsman.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] As Alexander approached, Bessus had his men murder Darius III and then declared himself Darius' successor, as Artaxerxes V, before retreating into Central Asia leaving Darius' body in the road to delay Alexander, who brought it to Persepolis for an honourable funeral.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Bessus would then create a coalition of his forces, to create an army to defend against Alexander.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Alexander generally kept the original Achaemenid administrative structure, leading some scholars to dub him as "the last of the Achaemenids".
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Upon Alexander's death in 323 BC, his empire was divided among his generals, the Diadochi, resulting in a number of smaller states.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] The largest of these, which held sway over the Iranian plateau, was the Seleucid Empire, ruled by Alexander's general Seleucus I Nicator.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Native Iranian rule would be restored by the Parthians of northeastern Iran over the course of the 2nd century BC through the Parthian Empire.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Several later Persian rulers, forming the *Frataraka* dynasty, are known to have acted as representatives of the Seleucids in the region of Fārs.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] They ruled from the end of the 3rd century BC to the beginning of the 2nd century BC, and Vahbarz or Vādfradād I obtained independence c.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] 150 BC, when Seleucid power waned in the areas of southwestern Persia and the Persian Gulf region.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] During an apparent transitional period, corresponding to the reigns of Vādfradād II and another uncertain king, no titles of authority appeared on the reverse of their coins.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] The earlier title *prtrk' zy alhaya* (Frataraka) had disappeared.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Under Dārēv I (Darios I) however, the new title of *mlk*, or king, appeared, sometimes with the mention of *prs* (Persis), suggesting that the kings of Persis had become independent rulers.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] When the Parthian Arsacid king Mithridates I (c.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] 171–138 BC) took control of Persis, he left the Persian dynasts in office, known as the Kings of Persis, and they were allowed to continue minting coins with the title of *mlk* ("King").
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Achaemenid line would also be carried on through the Kingdom of Pontus, based in the Pontus region of northern Asia Minor.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] This Pontic Kingdom, a state of Persian origin, may even have been directly related to Darius I and the Achaemenid dynasty.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] It was founded by Mithridates I in 281 BC and lasted until its conquest by the Roman Republic in 63 BC.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] The kingdom grew to its largest extent under Mithridates VI the Great, who conquered Colchis, Cappadocia, Bithynia, the Greek colonies of the Tauric Chersonesos and for a brief time the Roman province of Asia.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Thus, this Persian dynasty managed to survive and prosper in the Hellenistic world while the main Persian Empire had fallen.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Despite Greek influence on the Kingdom of Pontus, Pontics continued to maintain their Achaemenid lineage.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Both the later dynasties of the Parthians and Sasanians would on occasion claim Achaemenid descent.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Recently there has been some corroboration for the Parthian claim to Achaemenid ancestry via the possibility of an inherited disease (neurofibromatosis) demonstrated by the physical descriptions of rulers and from the evidence of familial disease on ancient coinage.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus the Great founded the empire as a multi-state empire, governed from four capital cities: Pasargadae, Babylon, Susa and Ecbatana.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Achaemenids allowed a certain amount of regional autonomy in the form of the satrapy system.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] A satrapy was an administrative unit, usually organized on a geographical basis.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] A 'satrap' (governor) was the governor who administered the region, a 'general' supervised military recruitment and ensured order, and a 'state secretary' kept the official records.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] The general and the state secretary reported directly to the satrap as well as the central government.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] At differing times, there were between 20 and 30 satrapies.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus the Great created an organized army including the Immortals unit, consisting of 10,000 highly trained soldiers Cyrus also formed an innovative postal system throughout the empire, based on several relay stations called Chapar Khaneh.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Persepolis Administrative Archives provide many insights into the Achaemenid government system.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Found at Persepolis in the 1930s, they are mostly in Elamite; the remains of more than 10,000 of these cuneiform documents have been uncovered.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Aramaic is represented by about 1,000 or more original records.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Only one tablet in Old Persian has been identified so far.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Also, many seals and seal impressions are found in these Persepolis archives.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] These documents represent administrative activity and flow of data in Persepolis over more than fifty consecutive years (509–457 BC).
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian daric was the first gold coin which, along with a similar silver coin, the siglos, introduced the bimetallic monetary standard of the Achaemenids, which has continued until today.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] This was accomplished by Darius I, who reinforced the empire and expanded Persepolis as a ceremonial capital; he revolutionized the economy by placing it on the silver and gold coinage.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Darius also introduced a regulated and sustainable tax system that was precisely tailored to each satrapy, based on their supposed productivity and their economic potential.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] For instance, Babylon was assessed for the highest amount and for a startling mixture of commodities – 1,000 silver talents, four months' supply of food for the army.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] India was clearly already fabled for its gold; Egypt was known for the wealth of its crops; it was to be the granary of the Persian Empire (as later of Rome's) and was required to provide 120,000 measures of grain in addition to 700 talents of silver.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] This was exclusively a tax levied on subject peoples.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] There is evidence that conquered and rebellious enemies could be sold into slavery.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Alongside its other innovations in administration and taxation, the Achaemenids may have been the first government in the ancient Near East to register private slave sales and tax them using an early form of sales tax.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Other accomplishments of Darius' reign included the codification of the *dāta* (a universal legal system which would become the basis of later Iranian law), and the construction of a new capital at Persepolis.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Under the Achaemenids, trade was extensive and there was an efficient infrastructure that facilitated the exchange of commodities in the far reaches of the empire.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Tariffs on trade, along with agriculture and tribute, were major sources of revenue for the empire.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] The satrapies were linked by a 2,500-kilometer highway, the most impressive stretch being the Royal Road from Susa to Sardis, built under the command of Darius I.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] It connected the Iranian Plateau to Central Asia and the Mediterranean.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] It featured stations and caravanserais at specific intervals.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] The relays of mounted couriers (the angarium) could reach the remotest of areas in fifteen days.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Herodotus observes that "there is nothing in the world that travels faster than these Persian couriers.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] Following Alexander's conquests, this highway allowed for the spread of cultural syncretic fusions like Greco-Buddhism into Central Asia and China, as well as empires like the Kushan, Indo-Greek and Parthian to profit from trade between East and West.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p01] This route was greatly rehabilitated and formalized during the Abbasid Caliphate, during which it developed into a major component of the famed Silk Road.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] Despite its humble origins in Persis, the empire reached an enormous size under the leadership of Cyrus the Great.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] Cyrus created a multi-state empire where he allowed regional rulers, satraps, to rule as his proxy over a certain designated area of his empire called a satrapy.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] The basic rule of governance was based upon loyalty and obedience of each satrapy to the central power, or the king, and compliance with tax laws.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] Cyrus managed to create a strong land army, using it to advance in his campaigns in Babylonia, Lydia, and Asia Minor, which after his death was used by his son Cambyses II, in Egypt against Psamtik III.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] Cyrus would die battling a local Iranian insurgency in the empire, before he could have a chance to develop a naval force.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] That task would fall to Darius I, who would officially give Persians their own royal navy to allow them to engage their enemies on multiple seas of this vast empire, from the Black Sea and the Aegean Sea, to the Persian Gulf, Ionian Sea and the Mediterranean Sea.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Achaemenid infantry consisted of three groups: the Immortals, the Sparabara, and the Takabara, though in the later years of the Achaemenid Empire, a fourth group, the Cardaces, were introduced.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Immortals were described by Herodotus as being heavy infantry, led by Hydarnes II, that were kept constantly at a strength of exactly 10,000 men.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] He claimed that the unit's name stemmed from the custom that every killed, seriously wounded, or sick member was immediately replaced with a new one, maintaining the numbers and cohesion of the unit.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] They had wicker shields, short spears, swords or large daggers, and bow and arrows.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] Underneath their robes they wore scale armour coats.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] The spear counterbalances of the common soldiery were of silver; to differentiate commanding ranks, the officers' spear butt-spikes were golden.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] Surviving Achaemenid colored glazed bricks and carved reliefs represent the Immortals as wearing elaborate robes, hoop earrings and gold jewellery, though these garments and accessories were most likely worn only for ceremonial occasions.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Sparabara were usually the first to engage in hand-to-hand combat with the enemy.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] Although not much is known about them today, it is believed that they were the backbone of the Persian army who formed a shield wall and used their two-metre-long spears to protect more vulnerable troops such as archers from the enemy.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Sparabara were taken from the full members of Persian society, were trained from childhood to be soldiers and when not called out to fight on campaigns in distant lands they practised hunting on the vast plains of Persia.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] However, when all was quiet and the *Pax Persica* held true, the Sparabara returned to normal life farming the land and grazing their herds.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] Because of this, they lacked true professional quality on the battlefield, yet they were well trained and courageous to the point of holding the line in most situations long enough for a counter-attack.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] They were armoured with quilted linen and carried large rectangular wicker shields as a form of light maneuverable defence.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] This, however, left them at a severe disadvantage against heavily armoured opponents such as the hoplite, and their two-metre-long spear was not able to give the Sparabara ample range to plausibly engage a trained phalanx.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] The wicker shields were able to effectively stop arrows but not strong enough to protect the soldier from spears.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] However, the Sparabara could deal with most other infantry, including trained units from the East.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Achaemenids relied heavily on archery.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] Major contributing nations were the Scythians, Medes, Persians, and the Elamites.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] The composite bow was used by the Persians and Medes, who adopted it from the Scythians and transmitted it to other nations, including the Greeks.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] Achaemenid armies typically used socketed, three-bladed (also known as trilobate or Scythian) arrowheads.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] These arrowheads were cast from leaded tin-bronze, which made them amenable to mass-production unlike the wrought iron arrowheads of the period that had to be individually forged.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Takabara were a rare unit who were a tough type of peltasts.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] They tended to fight with their own native weapons which would have included a crescent-shaped light wickerwork shield and axes as well as light linen cloth and leather.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Takabara were recruited from territories that incorporated modern Iran.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Persian cavalry was crucial for conquering nations and maintained its importance in the Achaemenid army to the last days of the Achaemenid Empire.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] The cavalry was separated into four groups.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] The chariot archers, horse cavalry, the camel cavalry, and the war elephants.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] In the later years of the Achaemenid Empire, the chariot archer had become merely a ceremonial part of the Persian army, yet in the early years of the Empire, their use was widespread.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] The chariot archers were armed with lances, bows, arrows, swords, and scale armour.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] The horses were also suited with scale armour similar to scale armour of the Sassanian cataphracts.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] The chariots would contain imperial symbols and decorations.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] The horses used by the Achaemenids for cavalry were often suited with scale armour, like most cavalry units.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] The riders often had the same armour as Infantry units, wicker shields, short spears, swords or large daggers, bow and arrow, and scale armour coats.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] The camel cavalry was different, because the camels and sometimes the riders, were provided little protection against enemies, yet when they were offered protection, they would have lances, swords, bow, arrow, and scale armour.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] The camel cavalry was first introduced into the Persian army by Cyrus the Great, at the Battle of Thymbra.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] The elephant was most likely introduced into the Persian army by Darius I after his conquest of the Indus Valley.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] Elephants may have been used in Greek campaigns by Darius and Xerxes I, but Greek accounts only mention 15 of them being used at the Battle of Gaugamela.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] Since its foundation by Cyrus, the Persian empire had been primarily a land empire with a strong army but void of any actual naval forces.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] By the 5th century BC, this was to change, as the empire came across Greek and Egyptian forces, each with their own maritime traditions and capabilities.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] Darius I was the first Achaemenid king to invest in a Persian fleet.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] Even by then no true "imperial navy" had existed either in Greece or Egypt.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] Persia would become the first empire, under Darius, to inaugurate and deploy the first regular imperial navy.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] Despite this achievement, the personnel for the imperial navy would not come from Iran, but were often Phoenicians (mostly from Sidon), Egyptians and Greeks chosen by Darius the Great to operate the empire's combat vessels.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] At first the ships were built in Sidon by the Phoenicians; the first Achaemenid ships measured about 40 meters in length and 6 meters in width, able to transport up to 300 Persian troops at any one trip.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] Soon, other states of the empire were constructing their own ships, each incorporating slight local preferences.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] The ships eventually found their way to the Persian Gulf and Persian naval forces laid the foundation for a strong Persian maritime presence there.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] Persians also had ships often of a capacity 100 to 200 troops patrolling the empire's various rivers including the Karun, Tigris and Nile in the west, as well as the Indus.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Achaemenid navy established bases located along the Karun, and in Bahrain, Oman, and Yemen.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Persian fleet was not only used for peace-keeping purposes along the Karun but also opened the door to trade with India via the Persian Gulf.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] Darius's navy was in many ways a world power at the time, but it would be Artaxerxes II who in the summer of 397 BC would build a formidable navy, as part of a rearmament which would lead to his decisive victory at Knidos in 394 BC, re-establishing Achaemenid power in Ionia.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] Artaxerxes II would also use his navy to later on quell a rebellion in Egypt.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] The construction material of choice was wood, but some armoured Achaemenid ships had metallic blades on the front, often meant to slice enemy ships using the ship's momentum.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] Naval ships were also equipped with hooks on the side to grab enemy ships, or to negotiate their position.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] The ships were propelled by sails or manpower.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] The ships the Persians created were unique.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] As far as maritime engagement, the ships were equipped with two mangonels that would launch projectiles such as stones, or flammable substances.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] Xenophon describes his eyewitness account of a massive military bridge created by joining 37 Persian ships across the Tigris.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Persians used each boat's buoyancy to support a connected bridge above which supply could be transferred.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] Herodotus also gives many accounts of the Persians using ships to build bridges.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] Darius I, in an attempt to subdue the Scythian horsemen north of the Black Sea, crossed over at the Bosphorus, using an enormous bridge made by connecting Achaemenid boats, then marched up to the Danube, crossing it by means of a second boat bridge.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] The bridge over the Bosphorus essentially connected the nearest tip of Asia to Europe, encompassing at least some 1000 meters of open water if not more.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] Years later, a similar boat bridge would be constructed by Xerxes I, in his invasion of Greece.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] Although the Persians failed to capture the Greek city-states completely, the tradition of maritime involvement was carried down by the Persian kings, most notably Artaxerxes II.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] Years later, when Alexander invaded Persia and during his advancement into India, he took a page from the Persian art of war, by having Hephaestion and Perdiccas construct a similar boat-bridge at the Indus river in India in the spring of 327 BC.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] They all had the same trilingual inscription (DPh inscription).
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] During the reign of Cyrus II and Darius I, and as long as the seat of government was still at Susa in Elam, the language of the chancellery was Elamite.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] This is primarily attested in the Persepolis fortification and treasury tablets that reveal details of the day-to-day functioning of the empire.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] In the grand rock-face inscriptions of the kings, the Elamite texts are always accompanied by Akkadian (Babylonian dialect) and Old Persian inscriptions, and it appears that in these cases that the Elamite texts are translations of the Old Persian ones.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] It is then likely that although Elamite was used by the capital government in Susa, it was not a standardized language of government everywhere in the empire.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] The use of Elamite is not attested after 458 BC.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] Following the conquest of Mesopotamia, the Aramaic language (as used in that territory) was adopted as a "vehicle for written communication between the different regions of the vast empire with its different peoples and languages.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] In 1955, Richard Frye questioned the classification of Imperial Aramaic as an official language, noting that no surviving edict expressly and unambiguously accorded that status to any particular language.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] Frye reclassifies Imperial Aramaic as the *lingua franca* of the Achaemenid empire, suggesting that the use of Aramaic language in Achaemenid empire was more widespread than generally thought.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] Many centuries after the fall of the empire, Aramaic script and—as ideograms—Aramaic vocabulary would survive as the essential characteristics of the Pahlavi writing system.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] Although Old Persian also appears on some seals and art objects, that language is attested primarily in the Achaemenid inscriptions of Western Iran, suggesting then that Old Persian was the common language of that region.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] When the occasion demanded, Achaemenid administrative correspondence was conducted in Greek, making it a widely used bureaucratic language.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] Even though the Achaemenids had extensive contacts with the Greeks and vice versa, and had conquered many of the Greek-speaking areas both in Europe and Asia Minor during different periods of the empire, the native Old Iranian sources provide no indication of Greek linguistic influence.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] However, there is plenty of evidence (in addition to the accounts of Herodotus) that Greeks, apart from being deployed and employed in the core regions of the empire, also evidently lived and worked in the heartland of the Achaemenid Empire, namely Iran.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] For example, Greeks were part of the various ethnicities that constructed Darius' palace in Susa, apart from the Greek inscriptions found nearby there, and one short Persepolis tablet written in Greek.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] Herodotus mentions that the Persians were invited to great birthday feasts (Herodotus, *Histories* 8), which would be followed by many desserts, a treat which they reproached the Greeks for omitting from their meals.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] He also observed that the Persians drank wine in large quantities and used it even for counsel, deliberating on important affairs when drunk, and deciding the next day, when sober, whether to act on the decision or set it aside.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] Religious toleration has been described as a "remarkable feature" of the Achaemenid Empire.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Hebrew Bible reports that Persian king Cyrus the Great released the Jewish people from the Babylonian captivity in 539–530 BC and permitted them to return to their homeland.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] Cyrus the Great assisted in the restoration of the sacred places of various cities, including to rebuild the Israelites’ Temple in Jerusalem.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] It was during the Achaemenid period that Zoroastrianism reached southwestern Iran, where it came to be accepted by the rulers and through them became a defining element of Persian culture.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] The religion was not only accompanied by a formalization of the concepts and divinities of the traditional Iranian pantheon but also introduced several novel ideas, including that of free will.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] Mithra was worshipped in the Empire; his temples and symbols were the most widespread, most people bore names related to him and most festivals were dedicated to him.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] During the reign of Artaxerxes I and Darius II, the Greek historian Herodotus wrote: "[the Persians] have no images of the gods, no temples nor altars, and consider the use of them a sign of folly.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] This comes, I think, from their not believing the gods to have the same nature with men, as the Greeks imagine." He claims the Persians offer sacrifice to: "the sun and moon, to the earth, to fire, to water, and to the winds.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] These are the only gods whose worship has come down to them from ancient times.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] At a later period, they began the worship of Urania, which they borrowed from the Arabians and Assyrians.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Babylonian scholar and priest Berosus records—although writing over seventy years after the reign of Artaxerxes II—that the emperor had been the first to make cult statues of divinities and have them placed in temples in many of the major cities of the empire.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] Berosus also substantiates Herodotus when he says the Persians knew of no images of gods until Artaxerxes II erected those images.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] On the means of sacrifice, Herodotus adds "they raise no altar, light no fire, pour no libations." Herodotus also observed that "no prayer or offering can be made without a magus present".
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] The position of women in the Achaemenid Empire varied depending on the culture to which they belonged and therefore differed by region.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] The hierarchy of royal women at the Persian court was ranked as follows: the king's mother, then the queen, the king's daughters, the king's concubines, and the other women of the royal palace.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] The king normally married a female member of the royal family or a Persian noblewoman related to a satrap or another important Persian man; it was permitted for members of the royal family to marry relatives, but there is no evidence for marriage between closer family members than half-siblings.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] The king's concubines were often either slaves, sometimes prisoners of war, or foreign princesses, whom the king did not marry because they were foreigners, and whose children did not have the right to inherit the throne.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] Greek sources accuse the king of having hundreds of concubines secluded in a harem.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] There is no archeological evidence supporting the existence of a harem, or the seclusion of women from contact with men, at the Persian court.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] The royal women joined the king at breakfast and dinner and accompanied him on his journeys.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] They may have participated in the royal hunt, as well as during the royal banquets.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] Herodotus relates how the Persian envoys at the Macedonian court demanded the presence of women during a banquet because it was the custom for women to participate in the banquets in their own country.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] The queen may have attended the king's audience, and archeological evidence shows that she gave her own audiences, at least for female supplicants.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] Royal women and noblewomen at court could travel on their own, accompanied by both male and female staff, own and manage their own fortune, land, and business.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] Depictions of Persian women show them with long dresses and veils which did not cover their faces or their hair, only flowing down over their neck at the back of the head as an ornament.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] Royal and aristocratic Achaemenid women were given an education in subjects that did not appear compatible with seclusions, such as horsemanship and archery.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] Royal and aristocratic women held and managed vast estates and workshops and employed large numbers of servants and professional laborers.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] Royal and aristocratic women do not seem to have lived in seclusion from men, since it is known that they appeared in public and traveled with their husbands, participated in hunting and in feasts.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] The chief wife of a royal or aristocratic man did not live in seclusion, as it is clearly stated that wives customarily accompanied their husbands at dinner banquets.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] They left the banquet when the "women entertainers" came in and the men began "merrymaking".
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] No woman ever ruled the Achaemenid Empire, as monarch or as regent, but some queen's consorts are known to have had influence over the affairs of state, notably Atossa and Parysatis.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] There is not evidence of any women being employed as an official in the administration or within religious service; however, there are plenty of archeological evidence of women being employed as free labourers in Persepolis, where they worked alongside men.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] Women could be employed as the leaders of their workforce, known by the title *arraššara pašabena*, which were then given a higher salary than the male workers of their workforce.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] Female laborers were given less than men.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] Qualified workers within the crafts were given equal pay regardless of their sex.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] Women are abundant in religious context in the cuneiform sources from late Achaemenid and Hellenistic Babylon.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] Achaemenid architecture included large cities, temples, palaces, and mausolea such as the Tomb of Cyrus the Great.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] The quintessential feature of its architecture was its eclectic nature, with elements of Median, Assyrian, and Asiatic Greek all incorporated, yet maintaining a unique Persian identity seen in the finished products.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] Its influence pervades the regions ruled by the Achaemenids, from the Mediterranean shores to India, especially with its emphasis on monumental stone-cut design and gardens subdivided by water-courses.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] Achaemenid art includes frieze reliefs, metalwork such as the Oxus Treasure, decoration of palaces, glazed brick masonry, fine craftsmanship (masonry, carpentry, etc.), and gardening.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] Although the Persians drew artists from all corners of their empire, incorporating their styles and techniques, they did not merely produce a combination of styles, but a synthesis of a new, unique Persian style.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] One of the most remarkable examples of both Achaemenid architecture and art is the grand palace of Persepolis, and its detailed workmanship, coupled with its grand scale.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] Many Achaemenid rulers built tombs for themselves.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] The most famous, Naqsh-e Rostam, is an ancient necropolis located about 12 km north-west of Persepolis, with the tombs of four of the kings of the dynasty are carved in this mountain: Darius I, Xerxes I, Artaxerxes I and Darius II.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] Other kings constructed their own tombs elsewhere.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] Artaxerxes II and Artaxerxes III preferred to carve their tombs beside their spring capital Persepolis.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] The left tomb belongs to Artaxerxes II and the right tomb belongs to Artaxerxes III, the last Achaemenid king to have a tomb.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] The tomb of the founder of the Achaemenid dynasty, Cyrus the Great, was built in Pasargadae (now a world heritage site).
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Achaemenid Empire has been referred to as the first “world empire” as it contained in the words of Persian kings “many people and many languages”.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] The diverse groups which made up the empire enjoyed a great deal of legal and cultural autonomy.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Achaemenid Empire has also left a lasting impression on the heritage and cultural identity of Asia and the Middle East, and influenced the development and structure of future empires.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] In fact, the Greeks, and later on the Romans, adopted the best features of the Persian method of governing an empire.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Persian model of governance was particularly formative in the expansion and maintenance of the Abbasid Caliphate, whose rule is widely considered the period of the Islamic Golden Age.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Achaemenid Empire is noted in Western history as the antagonist of the Greek city-states during the Greco-Persian Wars and for the emancipation of the Jewish exiles in Babylon.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] The historical mark of the empire went far beyond its territorial and military influences and included cultural, social, technological and religious influences as well.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] For example, many Athenians adopted Achaemenid customs in their daily lives in a reciprocal cultural exchange, some being employed by or allied to the Persian kings.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] The impact of the Edict of Cyrus is mentioned in Judeo-Christian texts, and the empire was instrumental in the spread of Zoroastrianism as far east as China.
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] The empire also set the tone for the politics, heritage and history of Iran (also known as Persia).
[src:iron-age/achaemenid-empire-p02] Hegel in his work *The Philosophy of History* introduces the Persian Empire as the "first empire that passed away" and its people as the "first historical people" in history.
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] Around 5,000 BC, peoples descending from migrant Greek Neolithic populations reached the northern European plain in modern-day France and Germany; they reached Britain some 1000 years later.
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] Once in the Balkans, the Aegean EEFs appear to have divided into two wings: one which expanded further north into Europe along the Danube (Linear Pottery culture), and another which headed west along the Mediterranean (Cardial Ware) into the Iberian Peninsula.
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] Descendants of this latter group eventually migrated into Britain.
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] Previously, these areas were populated by Western Hunter-Gatherer represented by the Cheddar Man.
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] The Chalcolithic (Copper Age) began in Europe around 5500 BC.
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] Chalcolithic Europeans began to erect megaliths in this period.
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] Commerce was practiced to some extent in very early times, as is shown by the distribution of Melian obsidian over all the Aegean area.
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] Cretan vessels appeared to be exported to Melos, Egypt, and the Greek mainland.
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] In particular, Melian vases, eventually, found their way to Crete.
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] After 1600 BC, there was commerce with Egypt, and Aegean goods found their way to all coasts of the Mediterranean.
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] No traces of currency have come to light, excluding certain axeheads.
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] These axeheads were too small for practical use.
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] Standard weights have been found, as well as representations of ingots.
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] The Aegean written documents have not yet been proven (by being found outside the area) to be epistolary (letter writing) correspondence with other countries.
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] Representations of ships are not common, but several have been observed on Aegean gems, gem-sealings, frying pans, and vases.
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] These vases feature ships of low free-board, with masts and oars.
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] Familiarity with the sea is proved by the free use of marine motifs in decoration.
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] The most detailed illustrations are to be found on the 'ship fresco' at Akrotiri on the island of Thera (Santorini) preserved by the ash fall from the volcanic eruption which destroyed the town there.
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] Discoveries, later in the 20th century, of sunken trading vessels such as those at Uluburun and Cape Gelidonya off the south coast of Turkey have brought forth an enormous amount of new information about that culture.
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] For details of monumental evidence the articles on Crete, Mycenae, Tiryns, Troad, Cyprus, etc., must be consulted.
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] The most representative site explored up to now is Knossos (see Crete) which has yielded not only the most various but the most continuous evidence from the Neolithic age to the twilight of classical civilization.
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] Next in importance come Hissarlik, Mycenae, Phaestus, Hagia Triada, Tiryns, Phylakope, Palaikastro and Gournia.
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] Mycenae and Tiryns are the two principal sites on which evidence of a prehistoric civilization was remarked long ago by the ancient Greeks.
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] The curtain-wall and towers of the Mycenaean citadel, its gate with heraldic lions, and the great "Treasury of Atreus" had borne silent witness for ages before Heinrich Schliemann's time.
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] However, they were regarded as a crude precursor of later Greek culture.
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] It was not until Schliemann's excavations that Mycenaean culture attracted serious scholarly attention.
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] There had been, however, a good deal of other evidence available before 1876, which, had it been collated and seriously studied, might have discounted the sensation that the discovery of the citadel graves eventually made.
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] For instance, scholars had noted that tributaries appearing in Egyptian art resembled modern Greeks, but were unable to definitely recognize them as such.
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] Nor did the Aegean objects which were lying obscurely in museums in 1870, or thereabouts, provide a sufficient test of the real basis underlying the Hellenic myths of the Argolid, the Troad and Crete, to cause these to be taken seriously.
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] Aegean vases have been exhibited both at Sèvres and Neuchatel since about 1840, the provenance (i.e. source or origin) being in the one case Phylakope in Melos, in the other Cephalonia.
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] Newton demonstrated these to be no strayed Phoenician products.
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] In 1866 primitive structures were discovered on the island of Therasia by quarrymen extracting pozzolana, a siliceous volcanic ash, for the Suez Canal works.
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] When this discovery was followed up in 1870, on the neighbouring Santorini (Thera), by representatives of the French School at Athens, much pottery of a class now known immediately to precede the typical late Aegean ware, and many stone and metal objects, were found.
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] These were dated by the geologist Ferdinand A.
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] Fouqué, somewhat arbitrarily, to 2000 BC, by consideration of the superincumbent eruptive stratum.
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] Nor was a connection immediately detected between them and the objects found four years later in a tomb at Menidi in Attica and a rock-cut "bee-hive" grave near the Argive Heraeum.
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] Even Schliemann's initial excavations at Hissarlik in the Troad did not excite surprise.
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] However, the "Burnt City" now known as Troy II, revealed in 1873, with its fortifications and vases, and a hoard of gold, silver, and bronze objects, which the discoverer connected with it, began to arouse curiosity both among scholars and the general public.
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] With Schliemann's excavations at Mycenae, interest in prehistoric Greece exploded.
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] It was recognized that the character of both the fabric and the decoration of the Mycenaean objects was not that of any previously known style.
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] A wide range in space was proved by the identification of the Inselsteine and the Ialysus vases with the new style, and a wide range in time by collation of the earlier Theraean and Hissarlik discoveries.
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] Many scholars were struck by potential resemblances between objects described by Homer and Mycenaean artifacts.
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] Schliemann resumed excavations at Hissarlik in 1878, and greatly increased our knowledge of the lower strata, but did not recognize the Aegean remains in his "Lydian" city now known as Late Bronze Age Troy.
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] These were not to be fully revealed until Dr.
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] Wilhelm Dorpfeld, who had become Schliemann's assistant in 1879, resumed the work at Hissarlik in 1892 after Schliemann's death.
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] But by laying bare in 1884 the upper stratum of remains on the rock of Tiryns, Schliemann made a contribution to our knowledge of prehistoric domestic life which was amplified two years later by Christos Tsountas's discovery of the palace at Mycenae.
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] Schliemann's work at Tiryns was not resumed till 1905, when it was proved, as had long been suspected, that an earlier palace underlies the one he had exposed.
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] From 1886 dates the finding of Mycenaean sepulchres outside the Argolid, from which, and from the continuation of Tsountas's exploration of the buildings and lesser graves at Mycenae, a large treasure, independent of Schliemann's princely gift, has been gathered into the National Museum at Athens.
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] In that year tholos-tombs, most already pillaged but retaining some of their furniture, were excavated at Arkina and Eleusis in Attica, at Dimini near Volos in Thessaly, at Kampos on the west of Mount Taygetus, and at Maskarata in Cephalonia.
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] During the Acropolis excavations in Athens, which terminated in 1888, many potsherds of the Mycenaean style were found; but Olympia had yielded either none, or such as had not been recognized before being thrown away, and the temple site at Delphi produced nothing distinctively Aegean (in dating).
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] The American explorations of the Argive Heraeum, concluded in 1895, also failed to prove that site to have been important in the prehistoric time, though, as was to be expected from its neighbourhood to Mycenae itself, there were traces of occupation in the later Aegean periods.
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] Prehistoric research had now begun to extend beyond the Greek mainland.
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] Certain central Aegean islands, Antiparos, Ios, Amorgos, Syros and Siphnos, were all found to be singularly rich in evidence of the Middle-Aegean period.
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] The series of Syran-built graves, containing crouching corpses, is the best and most representative that is known in the Aegean.
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] Melos, long marked as a source of early objects but not systematically excavated until taken in hand by the British School at Athens in 1896, yielded at Phylakope remains of all the Aegean periods, except the Neolithic.
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] A map of Cyprus in the later Bronze Age (such as is given by J.
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] Richter in Catalogue of the Cyprus Museum) shows more than 25 settlements in and about the Mesaorea district alone, of which one, that at Enkomi, near the site of Salamis, has yielded the richest Aegean treasure in precious metal found outside Mycenae.
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] In Egypt in 1887, Flinders Petrie found painted sherds of Cretan style at Kahun in the Fayum, and farther up the Nile, at Tell el-Amarna, chanced on bits of no fewer than 800 Aegean vases in 1889.
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] There have now been recognized in the collections at Cairo, Florence, London, Paris and Bologna several Egyptian imitations of the Aegean style which can be set off against the many debts which the centres of Aegean culture owed to Egypt.
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] Two Aegean vases were found at Sidon in 1885, and many fragments of Aegean and especially Cypriot pottery have been found during recent excavations of sites in Philistia by the Palestine Fund.
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] Orsi excavated the Sicel cemetery near Lentini in 1877, has proved a mine of early remains, among which appear in regular succession Aegean fabrics and motives of decoration from the period of the second stratum at Hissarlik.
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] Sardinia has Aegean sites, for example, at Abini near Teti; and Spain has yielded objects recognized as Aegean from tombs near Cádiz and from Saragossa.
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] One land, however, has eclipsed all others in the Aegean by the wealth of its remains of all the prehistoric ages— Crete; and so much so that, for the present, we must regard it as the fountainhead of Aegean civilization, and probably for long its political and social centre.
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] The island first attracted the notice of archaeologists by the remarkable archaic Greek bronzes found in a cave on Mount Ida in 1885, as well as by epigraphic monuments such as the famous law of Gortyna (also called Gortyn).
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] But the first undoubted Aegean remains reported from it were a few objects extracted from Cnossus by Minos Kalokhairinos of Candia in 1878.
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] These were followed by certain discoveries made in the S. plain Messara by F.
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] Unsuccessful attempts at Cnossus were made by both W.
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] Evans, coming on the scene in 1893, travelled in succeeding years about the island picking up trifles of unconsidered evidence, which gradually convinced him that greater things would eventually be found.
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] He obtained enough to enable him to forecast the discovery of written characters, till then not suspected in Aegean civilization.
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] The revolution of 1897–1898 opened the door to wider knowledge, and much exploration has ensued, for which see Crete.
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] Thus the "Aegean Area" has now come to mean the Archipelago with Crete and Cyprus, the Hellenic peninsula with the Ionian islands, and Western Anatolia.
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] Evidence is still wanting for the Macedonian and Thracian coasts.
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] Offshoots are found in the western Mediterranean area, in Sicily, Italy, Sardinia and Spain, and in the eastern Mediterranean area in Syria and Egypt.
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] Regarding the Cyrenaica, we are still insufficiently informed.
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] The final collapse of the Mycenaean civilisation appears to have occurred about 1200 BC.
[src:iron-age/aegean-civilization] Iron took the place of bronze, cremation took the place of burial of the dead, and writing was lost.
[src:iron-age/african-great-lakes] The **African Great Lakes** (Swahili: *Maziwa Makuu*; Kinyarwanda: *Ibiyaga bigari*) are a series of lakes constituting the part of the Rift Valley lakes in and around the East African Rift.
[src:iron-age/african-great-lakes] Collectively, they contain 31,000 km3 (7,400 mi3) of water, which is more than either Lake Baikal or the North American Great Lakes.
[src:iron-age/african-great-lakes] This total constitutes about 25% of the planet's unfrozen surface fresh water.
[src:iron-age/african-great-lakes] The large rift lakes of Africa are the ancient home of great biodiversity, and 10% of the world's fish species live in this region.
[src:iron-age/african-great-lakes] Countries in the area which are bounded by the lakes of the Great Lakes region include Burundi, the Democratic Republic of the Congo, Ethiopia, Kenya, Malawi, Mozambique, Rwanda, Tanzania, Uganda and Zambia.
[src:iron-age/african-great-lakes] The following are included on most lists of the African Great Lakes, grouped by drainage basin.
[src:iron-age/african-great-lakes] The exact number of lakes considered part of the African Great Lakes varies by list, and may include smaller lakes in the rift valleys, especially if they are part of the same drainage basin as the larger lakes, such as Lake Kyoga.
[src:iron-age/african-great-lakes] The Great Lakes region (rarely: *Greater* Lakes region) consists of ten riparian countries: Burundi, the Democratic Republic of the Congo, Ethiopia, Kenya, Malawi, Mozambique, Rwanda, Tanzania, Uganda, and Zambia.
[src:iron-age/african-great-lakes] The adjective *interlacustrine* ("between lakes") can refer to the region, or more specifically, the nations or area bounded by the lakes.
[src:iron-age/african-great-lakes] The Swahili language is the most commonly spoken language in the African Great Lakes region.
[src:iron-age/african-great-lakes] It also serves as a national or official language of five nations in the region: Tanzania, Kenya, Uganda, Rwanda, and the Democratic Republic of the Congo.
[src:iron-age/african-great-lakes] Because of its high population—estimated to be more than 50 million people in 2020—and the agricultural surplus in the region, the area became organized into a number of small states.
[src:iron-age/african-great-lakes] The most powerful of these monarchies were Buganda, Bunyoro, Karagwe, Rwanda, and Burundi.
[src:iron-age/african-great-lakes] Being the long-sought source of the Nile and the watershed triple point between the rivers Nile, Congo and Zambezi, the region had long been of interest to Europeans.
[src:iron-age/african-great-lakes] The first Europeans to arrive in the region in any numbers were Christian missionaries who had limited success in converting the locals, but did open the region to later colonization.
[src:iron-age/african-great-lakes] Increased contact with the rest of the world led to a series of devastating epidemics affecting both humans and livestock.
[src:iron-age/african-great-lakes] While seen as a region with great potential after independence, the Great Lakes region has suffered from civil war and conflict in the four decades around the turn of the 21st century (c.
[src:iron-age/african-great-lakes] In 2022, the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees commended Tanzania for consistently welcoming and aiding refugees from other countries in the region.
[src:iron-age/african-great-lakes] The highlands are relatively cool, with average temperatures ranging between 17 °C (63 °F) and 19 °C (66 °F) and abundant rainfall.
[src:iron-age/african-great-lakes] Major drainage basins include those of the Congo-Zaire, Nile, and Zambezi rivers, which drain into the Atlantic Ocean, Mediterranean Sea, and Indian Ocean, respectively.
[src:iron-age/african-great-lakes] Forests are dominant in the lowlands of the Congo-Zaire Basin, while grasslands and savannas (dry grasslands) are most common in the southern and eastern highlands.
[src:iron-age/african-great-lakes] Temperatures in the lowlands average about 35 °C (95 °F).
[src:iron-age/african-great-lakes] Around Lake Turkana, the climate is hot and very dry.
[src:iron-age/african-great-lakes] A short rainy season in October is followed by a longer one from April to May.
[src:iron-age/african-great-lakes] The Western Rift Valley lakes are freshwater and home to an extraordinary number of endemic species.
[src:iron-age/african-great-lakes] More than 1,500 cichlid fish species live in the lakes, as well as other fish families.
[src:iron-age/african-great-lakes] The lakes are also important habitats for a number of amphibian species.
[src:iron-age/african-great-lakes] Mammals include elephants, gorillas and hippopotamus.
[src:iron-age/african-great-lakes] The Lake Turkana area is home to hundreds of species of birds endemic to Kenya.
[src:iron-age/african-great-lakes] The East African rift system also serves as a flyway for migrating birds, bringing in hundreds more.
[src:iron-age/african-great-lakes] The birds are essentially supported by plankton masses in the lake, which also feed the fish there.
[src:iron-age/african-great-lakes] Vegetation ranges from rainforest to savanna grasses.
[src:iron-age/african-great-lakes] In some lakes, rapidly growing invasive plants, like the surface-choking water hyacinth and shore-clogging papyrus, are problems.
[src:iron-age/african-great-lakes] Water hyacinth have thus far affected only Lake Victoria.
[src:iron-age/african-great-lakes] Until 12 million years ago, the bountiful waters of the equatorial plateau either flowed west into the Congo River system or east to the Indian Ocean.
[src:iron-age/african-great-lakes] This was changed by the formation of the Great Rift Valley.
[src:iron-age/african-great-lakes] A rift is a weak place in Earth's crust due to the separation of two tectonic plates, often accompanied by a graben, or trough, in which lake water can collect.
[src:iron-age/african-great-lakes] This rift began when East Africa, impelled by currents in the mantle, began separating from the rest of Africa, moving to the northeast.
[src:iron-age/african-great-lakes] The basins that resulted from the geological uplifts filled with water that now flowed north.
[src:iron-age/african-great-lakes] Lake Victoria is not actually within the Rift Valley.
[src:iron-age/african-great-lakes] It occupies a depression between the Eastern and Western Rifts, formed by the uplift of the rifts to either of its sides.
[src:iron-age/african-great-lakes] Around two to three million years ago, Lake Turkana was larger and the area more fertile, making it a center for early hominids.
[src:iron-age/african-great-lakes] Richard Leakey led numerous anthropological excavations in the area, which yielded many important discoveries of hominin remains.
[src:iron-age/african-great-lakes] The two-million-year-old Skull 1470 was found in 1972.
[src:iron-age/african-great-lakes] It was originally thought to be *Homo habilis*, but some anthropologists have assigned it to a new species, *Homo rudolfensis*, named after the lake (previously known as Lake Rudolf).
[src:iron-age/african-great-lakes] In 1984, the Turkana Boy, a nearly complete skeleton of a *Homo erectus* boy was discovered.
[src:iron-age/african-great-lakes] In 1999, a 3,500,000-year-old skull was discovered there, named *Kenyanthropus platyops*, which means "flat-faced man of Kenya".
[src:iron-age/african-great-lakes] Fishing—primarily of tilapia species but also of Nile perch—provides the main livelihood for people in the region.
[src:iron-age/african-great-lakes] With four Great Lakes on its borders, Uganda ranks as one of the world's largest producers of freshwater fish.
[src:iron-age/african-great-lakes] The climate and rich volcanic soils in the highlands also sustain intensely cultivated croplands.
[src:iron-age/african-great-lakes] The economies of the Great Lakes region states have different structures and are at various stages of development.
[src:iron-age/african-great-lakes] The GDP real growth rate ranges from 1.8 percent in Burundi to 4.4 in the DRC.
[src:iron-age/african-great-lakes] GDP per capita fluctuates between $600 in DRC and Burundi and $800 in Uganda.
[src:iron-age/ages-of-man] The **Ages of Man** are the historical stages of human existence according to Greek mythology and its subsequent Roman interpretation.
[src:iron-age/ages-of-man] Both Hesiod and Ovid offered accounts of the successive ages of humanity, which tend to progress from an original, long-gone age in which humans enjoyed a nearly divine existence to the current age of the writer, in which humans are beset by innumerable pains and evils.
[src:iron-age/ages-of-man] In the two accounts that survive from Ancient Greece and Rome, this degradation of the human condition over time is indicated symbolically with metals of successively decreasing value, yet increasing hardness.
[src:iron-age/ages-of-man] The Greek poet Hesiod (between 750 and 650 BC) outlined his Five Ages in his poem *Works and Days* (lines 109–201).
[src:iron-age/ages-of-man] The Roman poet Ovid (1st century BC – 1st century AD) tells a similar myth of Four Ages in Book 1.89–150 of the *Metamorphoses*.
[src:iron-age/ages-of-man] His account is similar to Hesiod's, with the exception that he omits the Heroic Age.
[src:iron-age/ages-of-man] Ovid considers the Iron Age to be in the past, so he does not equate his time with the Iron Age.
[src:iron-age/ages-of-man] Plato in *Cratylus* recounts the golden race of men who came first.
[src:iron-age/ages-of-man] In the dialog, Socrates clarifies to Hermogenes that Hesiod did not mean men literally made of gold, but good and noble.
[src:iron-age/ages-of-man] Socrates describes these men as spirits or daemons upon the Earth.
[src:iron-age/ages-of-man] Since δαίμονες (*daimones*) is derived from δαήμονες (*daēmones*, meaning knowing or wise), they are beneficent, preventing ills, and guardians of mortals.
[src:iron-age/ages-of-man] According to *Bibliotheca*, attributed to Apollodorus (circa 2nd century BCE), the Bronze Age came to an end with the flood of Deucalion.
[src:iron-age/ages-of-man] In constrast, in *Eligies* (circa 1st century BCE), Propertius equates the same flood with the end of the Golden Age.
[src:iron-age/ages-of-man] These mythological ages are sometimes associated with historical timelines.
[src:iron-age/ages-of-man] In the chronology of Saint Jerome, the Golden Age lasts c.
[src:iron-age/ages-of-man] 1710 to 1674 BC, the Silver Age 1674 to 1628 BC, the Bronze Age 1628 to 1472 BC, the Heroic Age 1460 to 1103 BC, while Hesiod's Iron Age was considered as still ongoing by Saint Jerome in the fourth century AD.
[src:iron-age/ages-of-man] Modern historical periodisation such as the three-age system has reappropriated the terms Bronze Age and Iron Age to describe archaeological periods following the Stone Age based on predominant metallurgical practices.
[src:iron-age/ages-of-man] Congruently, the term Golden Age is used to describe a civilization during a historical highpoint, for example the Golden Age of India, Islamic Golden Age and the Han and Tang dynasties of China.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] 550 BC) is the final epoch of the three historical Metal Ages, after the Copper Age and Bronze Age.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] It has also been considered as the final age of the three-age division starting with prehistory (before recorded history) and progressing to protohistory (before written history).
[src:iron-age/iron-age] In this usage, it is preceded by the Stone Age (subdivided into the Paleolithic, Mesolithic and Neolithic) and Bronze Age.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] These concepts originated for describing Iron Age Europe and the ancient Near East.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] In the archaeology of the Americas, a five-period system is conventionally used instead; indigenous cultures there did not develop an iron economy in the pre-Columbian era, though some did work copper and silver.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] Indigenous metalworking arrived in Australia with European contact.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] Although meteoric iron has been used for millennia in many regions, the beginning of the Iron Age is defined locally around the world by archaeological convention when the production of smelted iron (especially steel tools and weapons) replaces their bronze equivalents in common use.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] In Anatolia and the Caucasus, or Southeast Europe, the Iron Age began c.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] In the ancient Near East, this transition occurred simultaneously with the Late Bronze Age collapse, during the 12th century BC.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] The technology soon spread throughout the Mediterranean basin region and to South Asia between the 12th and 11th centuries BC.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] Its further spread to Central Asia, Eastern Europe, and Central Europe was somewhat delayed, and Northern Europe was not reached until c. the 5th century BC.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] The Iron Age in India is stated as beginning with the ironworking Painted Grey Ware culture, dating from c.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] 1200 BC to the reign of Ashoka in the 3rd century BC.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] The term "Iron Age" in the archaeology of South, East, and Southeast Asia is more recent and less common than for western Eurasia.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] Africa did not have a universal "Bronze Age", and many areas transitioned directly from stone to iron.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] Some archaeologists believe that iron metallurgy was developed in sub-Saharan Africa independently from Eurasia and neighbouring parts of Northeast Africa as early as 2000 BC.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] The concept of the Iron Age ending with the beginning of the written historiographical record has not generalized well, as written language and steel use have developed at different times in different areas across the archaeological record.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] For instance, in China, written history started before iron smelting began, so the term is used infrequently for the archaeology of China.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] In Mesopotamia, written history predates iron smelting by hundreds of years.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] For the ancient Near East, the establishment of the Achaemenid Empire c.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] 550 BC is used traditionally and still usually as an end date; later dates are considered historical according to the record by Herodotus despite considerable written records now being known from well back into the Bronze Age.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] In Central and Western Europe, the conquests by the Roman Empire during the 1st century BC serve as marking the end of the Iron Age.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] The Germanic Iron Age of Scandinavia is considered to end c.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] AD 800, with the beginning of the Viking Age.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] The three-age system of Stone, Bronze, and Iron Ages was first used for the archaeology of Europe during the first half of the 19th century; by the latter half of the 19th century, it had been extended to the archaeology of the ancient Near East.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] Its name harks back to the mythological "Ages of Man" of Hesiod.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] As an archaeological era, it was first introduced to Scandinavia by Christian Jürgensen Thomsen during the 1830s.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] By the 1860s, it was embraced as a useful division of the "earliest history of mankind" in general and began to be applied in Assyriology.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] The development of the now-conventional periodization in the archaeology of the ancient Near East was developed during the 1920s and 1930s.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] Meteoric iron, a natural iron–nickel alloy, was used by various ancient peoples thousands of years before the Iron Age.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] The earliest-known meteoric iron artifacts are nine small beads dated to 3200 BC, which were found in burials at Gerzeh in Lower Egypt, having been shaped by careful hammering.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] The characteristic of an Iron Age culture is the mass production of tools and weapons made not just of found iron, but from smelted steel alloys with an added carbon content.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] Only with the capability of the production of carbon steel does ferrous metallurgy result in tools or weapons that are harder and lighter than bronze.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] Smelted iron appears sporadically in the archeological record from the middle Bronze Age.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] Whilst terrestrial iron is abundant naturally, temperatures above 1,250 °C (2,280 °F) are required to smelt it, impractical to achieve with the technology available commonly until the end of the second millennium BC.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] In addition to specially designed furnaces, ancient iron production required the development of complex procedures for the removal of impurities, the regulation of the admixture of carbon, and the invention of hot-working to achieve a useful balance of hardness and strength in steel.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] The earliest tentative evidence for iron-making is a small number of iron fragments with the appropriate amounts of carbon admixture found in the Proto-Hittite layers at Kaman-Kalehöyük in modern-day Turkey, dated to 2200–2000 BC.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] Similarly, recent archaeological remains of iron-working in the Ganges Valley in India have been dated tentatively to 1800 BC.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] Tewari (2003) concludes that "knowledge of iron smelting and manufacturing of iron artifacts was well known in the Eastern Vindhyas and iron had been in use in the Central Ganga Plain, at least from the early second millennium BC".
[src:iron-age/iron-age] African sites are revealing dates as early as 2000–1200 BC.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] However, some recent studies date the inception of iron metallurgy in Africa between 3000 and 2500 BC, with evidence existing for early iron metallurgy in parts of Nigeria, Cameroon, and Central Africa, from as early as around 2000 BC.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] The Nok culture of Nigeria may have practiced iron smelting from as early as 1000 BC, while the nearby Djenné-Djenno culture of the Niger Valley in Mali shows evidence of iron production from c.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] Iron technology across much of sub-Saharan Africa has an African origin dating to before 2000 BC.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] These findings confirm the independent invention of iron smelting in sub-Saharan Africa.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] Modern archaeological evidence identifies the start of large-scale global iron production about 1200 BC, marking the end of the Bronze Age.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] The Iron Age in Europe is often considered as a part of the Bronze Age collapse in the ancient Near East.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] Anthony Snodgrass suggests that a shortage of tin and trade disruptions in the Mediterranean about 1300 BC forced metalworkers to seek an alternative to bronze.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] Many bronze implements were recycled into weapons during that time, and more widespread use of iron resulted in improved steel-making technology and lower costs.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] When tin became readily available again, iron was cheaper, stronger and lighter, and forged iron implements superseded cast bronze tools permanently.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] In Central and Western Europe, the Iron Age lasted from c.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] 1 BC, beginning in pre-Roman Iron Age Northern Europe in c.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] 600 BC, and reaching Northern Scandinavian Europe about c.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] The Iron Age in the ancient Near East is considered to last from c.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] 550 BC (or 539 BC), roughly the beginning of historiography with Herodotus, marking the end of the proto-historical period.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] In China, because writing was developed first, there is no recognizable prehistoric period characterized by ironworking, and the Bronze Age China transitions almost directly into the Qin dynasty of imperial China.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] "Iron Age" in the context of China is used sometimes for the transitional period of c.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] 900 BC to 100 BC during which ferrous metallurgy was present even if not dominant.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] The Iron Age in the ancient Near East is believed to have begun after the discovery of iron smelting and smithing techniques in Anatolia, the Caucasus or Southeast Europe c.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] The earliest bloomery smelting of iron is found at Tell Hammeh, Jordan c.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] The Early Iron Age in the Caucasus area is divided conventionally into two periods: Early Iron I (c.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] 1100 BC), and Early Iron II (10th–9th centuries BC).
[src:iron-age/iron-age] Many of the material culture traditions of the Late Bronze Age continued into the Early Iron Age.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] Thus, there is a sociocultural continuity during this transitional period.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] In Iran, the earliest actual iron artifacts were unknown until the 9th century BC.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] For Iran, the best studied archaeological site during this time period is Teppe Hasanlu.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] In the Mesopotamian states of Sumer, Akkad and Assyria, the initial use of iron dates to perhaps 3000 BC.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] One of the earliest smelted iron artifacts known is a dagger with an iron blade found in a Hattic tomb in Anatolia, dating from 2500 BC.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] The widespread use of iron weapons which replaced bronze weapons rapidly disseminated throughout the Near East by the beginning of the 1st millennium BC.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] The development of iron smelting was once attributed to the Hittites of Anatolia during the Late Bronze Age.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] As part of the Late Bronze Age and Early Iron Age, the Bronze Age collapse saw the slow, comparatively continuous spread of iron-working technology in the region.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] It was long believed that the success of the Hittite Empire during the Late Bronze Age had been based on the advantages entailed by the "monopoly" on ironworking at the time.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] Accordingly, the invading Sea Peoples would have been responsible for spreading the knowledge through that region.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] The idea of such a "Hittite monopoly" has been examined more thoroughly and no longer represents a scholarly consensus.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] While there are some iron objects from Bronze Age Anatolia, the number is comparable to iron objects found in Egypt and other places of the same time period; and only a small number of these objects are weapons.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] In the Black Pyramid of Abusir, dating before 2000 BC, Gaston Maspero found some pieces of iron.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] In the funeral text of Pepi I, the metal is mentioned.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] Iron metal is singularly scarce in collections of Egyptian antiquities.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] Bronze remained the primary material there until the conquest by the Neo-Assyrian Empire in 671 BC.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] The explanation of this would seem to be that the relics are in most cases the paraphernalia of tombs, the funeral vessels and vases, and iron being considered an impure metal by the ancient Egyptians it was never used in their manufacture of these or for any religious purposes.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] It was attributed to Seth, the spirit of evil who according to Egyptian tradition governed the central deserts of Africa.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] A sword bearing the name of pharaoh Merneptah as well as a battle axe with an iron blade and gold-decorated bronze shaft were both found in the excavation of Ugarit.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] A dagger with an iron blade found in Tutankhamun's tomb, 13th century BC, was examined recently and found to be of meteoric origin.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] In Europe, the Iron Age is the last stage of prehistoric Europe and the first of the protohistoric periods, which initially means descriptions of a particular area by Greek and Roman writers.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] For much of Europe, the period came to an abrupt local end after conquest by the Romans, though ironworking remained the dominant technology until recent times.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] Elsewhere it may last until the early centuries AD, and either Christianization or a new conquest during the Migration Period.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] Iron working was introduced to Europe during the late 11th century BC, probably from the Caucasus, and slowly spread northwards and westwards over the succeeding 500 years.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] The Iron Age did not start when iron first appeared in Europe but it began to replace bronze in the preparation of tools and weapons.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] It did not happen at the same time throughout Europe; local cultural developments played a role in the transition to the Iron Age.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] For example, the Iron Age of Prehistoric Ireland begins about 500 BC (when the Greek Iron Age had already ended) and finishes about 400 AD.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] The widespread use of the technology of iron was implemented in Europe simultaneously with Asia.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] The prehistoric Iron Age in Central Europe is divided into two periods based on the Hallstatt culture (early Iron Age) and La Tène (late Iron Age) cultures.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] Material cultures of Hallstatt and La Tène consist of 4 phases (A, B, C, D).
[src:iron-age/iron-age] The Iron Age in Europe is characterized by an elaboration of designs of weapons, implements, and utensils.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] Citânia de Briteiros, located in Guimarães, Portugal, is one of the examples of archaeological sites of the Iron Age.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] This settlement (fortified villages) covered an area of 3.8 hectares (9.4 acres), and served as a Celtiberian stronghold against Roman invasions.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] The site was researched by Francisco Martins Sarmento starting from 1874.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] A number of amphoras (containers usually for wine or olive oil), coins, fragments of pottery, weapons, pieces of jewelry, as well as ruins of a bath and its *pedra formosa* (lit.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] The Iron Age began in Central Asia with the Saka, an Eastern Iranian people who lived in present-day Xinjiang, between the 10th and the 7th centuries BC, attested at sites like the cemetery at Chawuhukou.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] The Pazyryk culture is an Iron Age archaeological culture (c.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] 6th–3rd centuries BC) identified by excavated artifacts and mummified humans found in the Siberian permafrost in the Altai Mountains.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] In China, Chinese bronze inscriptions are found around 1200 BC, preceding the development of iron metallurgy, which was known by the 9th century BC.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] Iron metallurgy reached the Yangtze valley in the late 6th century BC.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] The few objects were found at Changsha and Nanjing.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] The mortuary evidence suggests that the initial use of iron in Lingnan belongs to the mid-to-late Warring States period (from c.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] Important non-precious husi style metal finds include iron tools found at the tomb at Guwei-cun of the 4th century BC.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] The techniques used in Lingnan are a combination of bivalve moulds of distinct southern tradition and the incorporation of piece mould technology from the *Zhongyuan*.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] The products of the combination of these two periods are bells, vessels, weapons and ornaments, and the sophisticated cast.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] An Iron Age culture of the Tibetan Plateau has been associated tentatively with the Zhangzhung culture described by early Tibetan writings.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] In Japan, iron items, such as tools, weapons, and decorative objects, are postulated to have entered Japan during the late Yayoi period (c.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] 300 AD) or the succeeding Kofun period (c.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] 250 – 538 AD), most likely from the Korean Peninsula and China.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] Distinguishing characteristics of the Yayoi period include the appearance of new pottery styles and the start of intensive rice agriculture in paddy fields.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] Yayoi culture flourished in a geographic area from southern Kyūshū to northern Honshū.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] The Kofun and the subsequent Asuka periods are sometimes referred to collectively as the Yamato period; The word *kofun* is Japanese for the type of burial mounds dating from that era.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] Iron objects were introduced to the Korean peninsula through trade with chiefdoms and state-level societies bordering the Yellow Sea during the 4th century BC, at the end of the Warring States period, but before the beginning of the Western Han dynasty.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] Yoon proposes that iron was first introduced to chiefdoms located along North Korean river valleys that flow into the Yellow Sea such as the Cheongcheon and Taedong Rivers.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] Iron production quickly followed during the 2nd century BC, and iron implements came to be used by farmers by the 1st century in southern Korea.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] The earliest known cast-iron axes in southern Korea are found in the Geum River river basin.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] The time that iron production begins is the same time that complex chiefdoms of Proto-historic Korea emerged.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] The complex chiefdoms were the precursors of early states such as Silla, Baekje, Goguryeo, and Gaya Iron ingots were an important mortuary item and indicated the wealth or prestige of the deceased during this period.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] The early evidence of iron smelting predates the emergence of the Iron Age proper by several centuries.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] Iron was being used in Mundigak to manufacture some The history of metallurgy in the Indian subcontinent began prior to the 3rd millennium BC.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] Archaeological sites in India, such as Malhar, Dadupur, Raja Nala Ka Tila, Lahuradewa, Kosambi and Jhusi, Allahabad in present-day Uttar Pradesh show iron implements in the period 1800–1200 BC.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] As the evidence from the sites Raja Nala ka tila, Malhar suggest the use of Iron c.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] The extensive use of iron smelting is from Malhar and its surrounding area.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] This site is assumed as the center for smelted bloomer iron to this area due to its location in the Karamnasa River and Ganga River.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] This site shows agricultural technology as iron implements sickles, nails, clamps, spearheads, etc., by c.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] Archaeological excavations in Hyderabad show an Iron Age burial site.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] However, reviewing the claims of early uses of iron during c.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] The beginning of the 1st millennium BC saw extensive developments in iron metallurgy in India.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] Technological advancement and mastery of iron metallurgy were achieved during this period of peaceful settlements.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] One ironworking centre in East India has been dated to the 1st millennium BC.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] In Southern India (present-day Mysore) iron appeared as early as 12th to 11th centuries BC; these developments were too early for any significant close contact with the northwest of the country.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] The Indian Upanishads mention metallurgy. and the Indian Mauryan period saw advances in metallurgy.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] As early as 300 BC, certainly by 200 AD, high-quality steel was produced in southern India, by what would later be called the crucible technique.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] In this system, high-purity wrought iron, charcoal, and glass were mixed in a crucible and heated until the iron melted and absorbed the carbon.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] The protohistoric Early Iron Age in Sri Lanka lasted from 1000 BC to 600 BC.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] Radiocarbon dating evidence has been collected from Anuradhapura and Aligala shelter in Sigiriya.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] The Anuradhapura settlement is recorded to extend 10 ha (25 acres) by 800 BC and grew to 50 ha (120 acres) by 700–600 BC to become a town.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] The skeletal remains of an Early Iron Age chief were excavated in Anaikoddai, Jaffna.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] The name "Ko Veta" is engraved in Brahmi script on a seal buried with the skeleton and is assigned by the excavators to the 3rd century BC.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] Ko, meaning "King" in Tamil, is comparable to such names as Ko Atan and Ko Putivira occurring in contemporary Brahmi inscriptions in south India.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] It is also speculated that Early Iron Age sites may exist in Kandarodai, Matota, Pilapitiya and Tissamaharama.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] The earliest undisputed deciphered epigraphy found within the Indian subcontinent are the Edicts of Ashoka of the 3rd century BC, in the Brahmi script.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] However, more recent scholars have dated them to later periods.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] Archaeology in Thailand at sites Ban Don Ta Phet and Khao Sam Kaeo yielding metallic, stone, and glass artifacts stylistically associated with the Indian subcontinent suggest Indianization of Southeast Asia beginning between the 4th and 2nd centuries BC during the late Iron Age.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] In Philippines and Vietnam, the Sa Huynh culture showed evidence of an extensive trade network.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] Sa Huynh beads were made from glass, carnelian, agate, olivine, zircon, gold and garnet; most of these materials were not local to the region and were most likely imported.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] Han-dynasty-style bronze mirrors were also found in Sa Huynh sites.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] Conversely, Sa Huynh produced ear ornaments have been found in archaeological sites in Central Thailand, as well as the Orchid Island.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] Early evidence for iron technology in Sub-Saharan Africa can be found at sites such as KM2 and KM3 in northwest Tanzania and parts of Nigeria and the Central African Republic.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] Nubia was one of the relatively few places in Africa to have a sustained Bronze Age along with Egypt and much of the rest of North Africa.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] Archaeometallurgy originated in numerous centers of Africa; the centers of origin were located in West Africa, Central Africa, and East Africa; consequently, as these origin centers are located within inner Africa, these archaeometallurgical developments are thus native African technologies.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] Iron metallurgical development occurred 2631–2458 BC at Lejja, in Nigeria, 2136–1921 BC at Obui, in Central Africa Republic, 1895–1370 BC at Tchire Ouma 147, in Niger, and 1297–1051 BC at Dekpassanware, in Togo.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] Very early copper and bronze working sites in Niger may date as early as 1500 BC.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] There is also evidence of iron metallurgy in Termit, Niger from around this period.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] Nubia was a major manufacturer and exporter of iron after the expulsion of the Nubian dynasty from Egypt by the Assyrians in the 7th century BC.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] Though there is some uncertainty, some archaeologists believe that iron metallurgy was developed independently in sub-Saharan West Africa, separately from Eurasia and neighboring parts of North and Northeast Africa.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] Archaeological sites containing iron smelting furnaces and slag have also been excavated at sites in the Nsukka region of southeast Nigeria in what is now Igboland: dating to 2000 BC at the site of Lejja (Eze-Uzomaka 2009) and to 750 BC and at the site of Opi (Holl 2009).
[src:iron-age/iron-age] The site of Gbabiri (in the Central African Republic) has yielded evidence of iron metallurgy, from a reduction furnace and blacksmith workshop – with earliest dates of 896–773 BC and 907–796 BC, respectively.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] Similarly, smelting in bloomery-type furnaces appear in the Nok culture of central Nigeria by about 550 BC and possibly a few centuries earlier.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] Iron and copper working in Sub-Saharan Africa spread south and east from Central Africa in conjunction with the Bantu expansion, from the Cameroon region to the African Great Lakes in the 3rd century BC, reaching the Cape around 400 AD.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] However, iron working may have been practiced in central Africa as early as the 3rd millennium BC.
[src:iron-age/iron-age] Instances of carbon steel based on complex preheating principles were found to be in production around the 1st century AD in northwest Tanzania.
